<exercises>

  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Pour se pratiquer</title>
    
    
    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\cV</m> le cube
    <md>
    <mrow>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    et <m>\cR</m> le carré
    <md>
    <mrow>
    R=\Set{(x,y)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 1}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    et soit <m>f(x,y,z)</m> une fonction de classe <m>C^1</m>
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Utiliser le théorème fondamental du calcul pour montrer que
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(x,y,z)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    =\iint_{\cR}\! f(x,y,1)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
      -\! \iint_{\cR}\! f(x,y,0)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </li>
    <li>
    Utiliser le théorème de la divergence pour montrer que
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(x,y,z)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    =\iint_{\cR}\! f(x,y,1)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
      -\! \iint_{\cR}\! f(x,y,0)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution>
      <p> (a) Expressing the left hand side as an iterated integral,
    with <m>z</m> as the innermost integration variable, we have
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(x,y,z)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\left[\int_0^1\dee{z}\
                    \frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(x,y,z)\right]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\ \big[f(x,y,1)-f(x,y,0)\big]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip1in\text{by the fundamental theorem of calculus}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{\cR}\big[f(x,y,1)-f(x,y,0)\big]\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{\cR} f(x,y,1)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
      - \iint_{\cR} f(x,y,0)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) Define the vector field <m>\vF(x,y,z) = f(x,y,z)\,\vk </m>. Then the divergence
    of <m>\vF</m> is <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF(x,y,z) = \frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(x,y,z)</m>.
    The boundary of the cube <m>\cV</m> is the union of six faces
    <md>
    <mrow>
    S_1&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ z=1}\
       \text{with outward normal } \vn =\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_2&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ z=0}\
       \text{with outward normal } \vn =-\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_3&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1,\ y=1}\
       \text{with outward normal } \vn =\vj
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_4&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1,\ y=0}\
       \text{with outward normal } \vn =-\vj
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_5&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1,\ x=1}\
       \text{with outward normal } \vn =\vi
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_6&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant y\leqslant 1,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1,\ x=0}\
       \text{with outward normal } \vn =-\vi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="55%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cubeDT"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Observe that
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF\cdot\vn  = f\,\vk \cdot\vn  = \begin{cases} +f &amp;\text{on } S_1 \\
                                -f &amp;\text{on } S_2 \\
                                0  &amp;\text{on } S_3, S_4, S_5, S_6
                 \end{cases}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    So le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}(x,y,z)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF(x,y,z)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \iint_{\partial V} \vF\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
    =\sum_{j=1}^6  \iint_{S_j} \vF\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{S_1} f\ \dee{S}
         -\iint_{S_2} f\ \dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{\cR} f(x,y,1)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
      - \iint_{\cR} f(x,y,0)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Appliquer le théorème de la divergence à  <m>\vF=\phi\,\va</m>, où  <m>\va</m> est un vecteur constant arbitraire, pour montrer que
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\phi\,\dee{V}=\iint_{\partial V}\phi\,\vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    </li>
    <li>
    Montrer que le centre de gravité<m>(\bar x,\bar y,\bar z)</m> d'un solide  <m>\cV</m> de volume <m>|\cV|</m> est donné par
    <me>
    (\bar x,\bar y,\bar z)=\frac{1}{2|\cV| }\iint_{\partial V} (x^2+y^2+z^2)\,\vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution><p>
    (a) The divergence of <m>\phi\,\va</m> is
    <m>\vnabla\cdot(\phi\,\va)
    =\vnabla\phi\cdot\va+\phi\vnabla\cdot\va=\vnabla\phi\cdot\va</m>, since <m>\va</m> is
    constant. So, by
    le théorème de la divergence,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\partial V}\phi\,\va\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot(\phi\,\va)\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\phi\cdot\va\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\implies \left[\iint_{\partial V}\phi\vn \,\dee{S}
             -\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\phi\,\dee{V}\right]\cdot\va=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    This is true for all vectors <m>\va</m>. In particular, applying this with
    <m>\va=\vi ,\vj ,\vk </m>, we have that all three components of
    <m>\left[\iint_{\partial V}\phi\vn \,\dee{S}
             -\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\phi\,\dee{V}\right]</m> are zero.
    So
    <me>
    \iint_{\partial V}\phi\,\vn \,\dee{S}-\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\phi\,\dee{V}=0
    </me>
    </p>

    <p>(b) By part (a), with <m>\phi=x^2+y^2+z^2</m> and
    <m>\vnabla\phi = 2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +2z\,\vk </m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \frac{1}{2|\cV| }\iint_{\partial V} (x^2+y^2+z^2)\,\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\frac{1}{2|\cV| } \iiint_{\cV} (2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +2z\,\vk )\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=(\bar x,\bar y,\bar z)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>
   

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la sphère unité centrée à l'origine, avec le vecteur normal pointant vers l'extérieur. Si    <me>
    \vF(x,y,z)=\big(x,y,z^2\big)
    </me>
    calculer le flux de <m>\vF</m>à travers <m>\cS</m>
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
       directement, et
    </li>
    <li>
       en utilisant le théorème de la divergence.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (b) L'intégrale peut être évaluée trivialement en exploitant l'imparité de l'intégrande et le fait que  <m> \iiint_{\cV}\ \dee{V}=\text{Volume}(V)</m>.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{8\pi}{3}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
     (a) We'll parametrize the sphere using the spherical coordinates <m>\theta</m> and
    <m>\varphi</m>.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    x&amp;=\sin\varphi\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    y&amp;=\sin\varphi\sin\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    z&amp;=\cos\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    with <m>0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi</m>, <m>0\le\varphi\leqslant \pi</m>.
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
          \frac{\partial y}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
          \frac{\partial z}{\partial\theta}\Big)
    &amp;=\big(-\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
           \sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\varphi}\,,\,\frac{\partial y}{\partial\varphi}
                 \,,\, \frac{\partial z}{\partial\varphi}\Big)
    &amp;=(\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,-\sin\varphi)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>) yields
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\pm\Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
              \frac{\partial y}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
              \frac{\partial z}{\partial\theta}\Big)
    \times
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\varphi}\,,\,\frac{\partial y}{\partial\varphi}
       \,,\, \frac{\partial z}{\partial\varphi}\Big)
    \ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm \big(-\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
           \sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,0\big)
    \!\times\!
    (\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,-\sin\varphi)
    \ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm\big(-\sin^2\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              -\sin^2\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              -\sin\varphi\cos\varphi\big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\mp \sin\varphi \big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              \sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              \cos\varphi\big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\mp \sin\varphi \big(x(\theta,\varphi)\,,\,
              y(\theta,\varphi)\,,\,
              z(\theta,\varphi)\big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get an outward pointing normal we need the <m>+</m> sign, since then
    <m>\vn (\theta,\varphi)</m> is a positive multiple, namely <m>\sin\varphi</m>,
    times <m>\vr(\theta,\varphi)</m>. So, on <m>\cS</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
      &amp;= \sin\varphi \overbrace{\big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              \sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              \cos^2\varphi\big)}^{\vF}
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1.5in\cdot
          \big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              \sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              \cos\varphi\big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;= \sin\varphi\big(\sin^2\varphi\cos^2\theta
                 +\sin^2\varphi\sin^2\theta+\cos^3\varphi\big)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^\pi \dee{\varphi}\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin\varphi\big(\sin^2\varphi\cos^2\theta
    +\sin^2\varphi\sin^2\theta+\cos^3\varphi\big)\cr
    &amp;=\int_0^\pi \dee{\varphi}\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\
          \big(\sin^3\varphi + \sin\varphi\cos^3\varphi\big)\cr
    &amp;=2\pi \left\{\int_0^\pi \dee{\varphi}\ \sin^3\varphi
             \ +\ \left[-\frac{1}{4}\cos^4\varphi\right]^\pi_0 \right\}\cr
    &amp;=2\pi\int_0^\pi \dee{\varphi}\ \sin\varphi(1-\cos^2\varphi)
    =2\pi\left[-\cos\varphi+\frac{1}{3}\cos^3\varphi\right]_0^\pi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi\left[\frac{4}{3}\right]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{8\pi}{3}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) Let <m>\cV</m> be the interior of <m>\cS</m>. Then, by le théorème de la divergence,
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV}(1+1+2z)\ \dee{V}
    </me>
    By oddness under <m>z\rightarrow -z</m>, the <m>z</m> integral vanishes, so that
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =2\iiint_{\cV}\ \dee{V}
    =2\,\text{Volume}(V)
    =2\frac{4\pi}{3}
    =\frac{8\pi}{3}
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
     Calculer, de deux façons calculer
    <m>\iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m>, où  <m>\vF=z\,\vk </m>,
    <m>\cS</m> est la surface <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=a^2</m> et  <m>\vn </m> est le vecteur normal à <m>\cS</m> pointant vers l'extérieur.

    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    D'abord par un calcul de l'intégrale de surface;
    </li>
    <li>
    Puis en utilisant le théorème de la divergence.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Pour la partie (a), penser aux coordonnées sphériques.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a), (b) <m>\frac{4}{3}\pi a^3</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    (a) Let's use spherical coordinates. As <m>\cS</m> is the
    sphere of radius <m>a</m> centred on the origin,  we can parametrize it by
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vr(\theta,\varphi)
      &amp;=a\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
         +a\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
         + a\cos\varphi\,\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{\theta}
       &amp;=-a\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,\vi
         +a\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,\vj
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{\varphi}
       &amp;= \phantom{-}a\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
         +a\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
        -a\sin\varphi\,\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\pm\pdiff{\vr}{\theta}
       \times \pdiff{\vr}{\varphi}
        \ \dee{\theta}\, d\varphi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}   \vi  &amp;\vj  &amp;\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
                  -a\sin\varphi\sin\theta &amp; a\sin\varphi\cos\theta &amp; 0
    </mrow><mrow>
                  a\cos\varphi\cos\theta &amp; a\cos\varphi\sin\theta &amp; -a\sin\varphi
       \end{matrix}\right]  \dee{\theta}\, d\varphi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm\Big(-a^2\sin^2\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
              -a^2\sin^2\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
              -a^2\sin\varphi\cos\varphi\,\vk \Big)\ \dee{\theta}\, d\varphi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\mp a^2\sin\varphi \big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
              +\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
              +\cos\varphi\,\vk \Big)\ \dee{\theta}\, d\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    For the outward normal, we want the <m>+</m> sign, so
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= a^2\sin\varphi \big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
              +\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
              +\cos\varphi\,\vk \Big)\ \dee{\theta}\, d\varphi
    </mrow><mrow>
    \vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S} &amp;= z(\theta,\varphi)\,\vk \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
               = a^3 \sin\varphi\cos^2\varphi\ \dee{\theta}\,d\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= a^3\int_0^\pi d\varphi\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin\varphi\,\cos^2\varphi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi a^3 \int_0^\pi d\varphi \ \sin\varphi\,\cos^2\varphi
    =2\pi a^3\left[-\frac{1}{3}\cos^3\varphi\right]_0^\pi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{4}{3}\pi a^3
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) Call the solid <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant a^2</m>, <m>\cV</m>.
    As
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    =\pdiff{}{x}(0)
    +\pdiff{}{y}(0)
    +\pdiff{}{z}(z)
    =1
    </me>
    le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} \ \dee{V}
    =\text{Volume}(V)
    =\frac{4}{3}\pi a^3
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
     Soit
    <ul>
    <li>
    <m>\ \vF=zy^3\,\vi +yx\, \vj +(2z+y^2)\vk \ </m> et
    </li>
    <li>
     <m>\cV</m> la région de <m>\R^3</m> définie par
    <me>
    0\leqslant z\leqslant \frac{9-x^2-y^2}{9+x^2+y^2}
    </me>
    et
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\cD</m> la partie surface intégieur de <m>\cV</m>. Puisque <m>\frac{9-x^2-y^2}{9+x^2+y^2}</m> est positive pour<m>x^2+y^2 \lt  9</m> et négative pour  <m>x^2+y^2 \gt  9</m>, la surface inférieure est  <m>z=0</m>, <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 9</m>.
    </li>
    <li><p>
    Soit <m>\cS</m> la portion courbée du bord de <m>\cV</m>. Il s'agit de <m>z={9-x^2-y^2\over 9+x^2+y^2}</m>, <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 9</m>. Voici une esquisse
    </p>
    <sidebyside width="35%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/divThmA"/>
    </sidebyside>

    </li>
    </ul>
    Soit  <m>|\cV| </m> le volume de  <m>\cV</m>. Calculer, en termes de  <m>|\cV| </m>,
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    <m>\ds \iint_{D}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m> avec  <m>\vn </m> pointant vers le bas
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\ds \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}</m>
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\ds \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> avec <m>\vn </m> pointant vers l'extérieur
    </li>
    </ol>
    Utiliser le théorème de la divergence  pour répondre à moins une des questions  (a), (b) ou (c).
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (a) Penser aux coordonnées polaires.
    </p>

    <p>(b) Puisque <m>x</m> est impaire, <m>\iiint_{\cV} x\,\dee{V}=0</m>.
    </p>

    </hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>-\frac{81}{4}\pi</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>2|\cV| </m>  </p><p>
    (c) <m>2|\cV| +\frac{81}{4}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    (a)
    On <m>D</m>, <m>z=0</m> and
    <me>
    \vn =-\vk \qquad
    \dee{S}=\dee{x}\,\dee{y}\qquad
    \vF\cdot\vn =-y^2
    </me>
    so that
    <me>
    \iint_{D}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =-\iint_D y^2\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </me>
    Switching to polar coordinates
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{D}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=-\int_0^3 dr\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \big(r\sin\theta\big)^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\bigg[\int_0^3 dr\,r^3\bigg]\ \bigg[\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2\theta\bigg]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{3^4}{4}\ \bigg[\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\bigg]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{81}{4}\bigg[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\bigg]_0^{2\pi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{81}{4}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
    <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2 \theta\ \dee{\theta}</m>, see Example
    <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
    </p>

    <p>(b)
    Observe that <m>\vnabla\cdot \vF=x+2</m>. Since <m>x</m> is odd and <m>\cV</m> is invariant
    under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m>, we have <m>\iiint_{\cV} x\,\dee{V}=0</m> (more details
    below) so that
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} (x+2)\,\dee{V}
    =2\iiint_{\cV} \,\dee{V}
    =2|\cV|
    </me>
    Here are two more detailed arguments showing that <m>\iiint_{\cV} x\,\dee{V}=0</m>.
    </p>

    <p><em>Argument 1:</em> We may rewrite the equation
    <m>z=\frac{9-x^2-y^2}{9+x^2+y^2}</m> of the curved boundary of <m>\cV</m>
    as
    <me>
    z(9+x^2+y^2) = 9-x^2-y^2 \iff
    x^2+y^2 = \frac{9(1-z)}{1+z}
    </me>
    This is the equation of the circle of radius
    <m>r(z)=\sqrt{\frac{9(1-z)}{1+z}}</m> centred on <m>x=y=0</m>.
    So <m>z</m> runs from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>, and for each fixed <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant 1</m>,
    <m>y</m> runs from  <m>-r(z)</m> to <m>r(z)</m>
    and, for each fixed <m>y</m> and <m>z</m>, <m>x</m> runs from <m>-\sqrt{r(z)^2-y^2}</m>
    to <m>\sqrt{r(z)^2-y^2}</m>. So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV} x\,\dee{V}
    =\int_0^1 \dee{z}\int_{-r(z)}^{r(z)}\dee{y}
           \int_{-\sqrt{r(z)^2-y^2}}^{\sqrt{r(z)^2-y^2}} \dee{x}\ x
    =\int_0^1 \dee{z}\int_{-r(z)}^{r(z)}\dee{y}\ 0
    =0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since <m>\int_{-a}^a x\ \dee{x}=0</m> for any <m>a \gt 0</m>.
    </p>

    <p><em>Argument 2:</em>  As we have observed above, the
    curved boundary of <m>\cV</m> is <m>x^2+y^2 = \frac{9(1-z)}{1+z}</m> which
    is invariant under rotations about the <m>z</m>--axis. By that symmetry, the
    centroid of <m>\cV</m> lies on the <m>z</m>-axis. Recall that, for any solid <m>\cV</m>,
    the centroid of <m>\cV</m> is <m>(\bar x,\bar y,\bar z)</m> with
    <me>
    \bar x = \frac{\iiint_{\cV} x \dee{V}}{\iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}}\qquad
    \bar y = \frac{\iiint_{\cV} y \dee{V}}{\iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}}\qquad
    \bar z = \frac{\iiint_{\cV} z \dee{V}}{\iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}}
    </me>
    So
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV} x\,\dee{V} = \bar x\, \text{Volume}(V) =0 \qquad\text{and}\qquad
    \iiint_{\cV} y\,\dee{V} = \bar y\,  \text{Volume}(V) =0
    </me>
    </p>

    <p>(c)
    By le théorème de la divergence,
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}
    =\iint_{\partial V}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    +\iint_D\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    so that
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}
    -\iint_D\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =2|\cV| +\frac{81}{4}\pi
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Évaluer, par deux méthodes,  l'intégrale  <m>\iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m>, où <m>\vF=(x,y,1)</m>, <m>\cS</m> est la surface <m>z=1-x^2-y^2</m> pour <m>x^2 y^2 \leqslant 1</m>, et <m>\vn </m> est le vecteur normal pointant vers le haut.
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    D'abord par un calcul direct de l'intégrale de surface;
    </li>
    <li>
    Puis grace au  théorème de la divergence.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (a) Penser aux coordonnées polaires.
    </p>

    <p>(b) Le volume du solide peut être calculé au moyen de tranches horizontales minces.
    </p>

    </hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a), (b) <m>2\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    (a)  Let <m>G(x,y,z) = x^2+y^2+z</m>. Then the surface is <m>G(x,y,z)=1</m>
    and <m>\vnabla G(x,y,z) = 2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +\vk </m>  is upward pointing (i.e. the coefficient of
    <m>\vk </m> is positive)  so that, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSimplicit"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S}&amp;=\frac{\vnabla G}{\vnabla G\cdot\vk }\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    =\frac{2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +\vk }{1}\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=(2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +\vk )\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\big[x\,\vi +y\,\vj +\vk \big]\cdot
              \big[2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +\vk \big]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\big[2x^2+2y^2+1\big]\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Switching to polar coordinates
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =\int_0^1dr\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ (2r^2+1)
    =2\pi\left[\frac{2}{4} r^4+\frac{1}{2} r^2\right]_0^1
    =2\pi
    </me>
    </p>

    <p>(b) Call the solid <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant 1-x^2-y^2</m>, <m>\cV</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="40%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/divThmB"/>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
    Let  <m>D</m> denote the bottom surface of <m>\cV</m>.
    The disk <m>D</m> has radius <m>1</m>, area <m>\pi</m>, <m>z=0</m> and outward normal <m>-\vk </m>,
    so that
    <me>
    \iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =-\iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    =-\iint_{D}\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    =-\pi
    </me>
    As
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    =\pdiff{}{x}(x)
    +\pdiff{}{y}(y)
    +\pdiff{}{z}(1)
    =2
    </me>
    le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    -\iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} 2\ \dee{V} -(-\pi)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi + 2\iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To evaluate the volume <m>\iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}</m>, we slice the <m>\cV</m> into
    thin horizontal pancakes. Here is a sketch of the pancake at height
    <m>z</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="45%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/divThmC"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Its cross-section is a circular disk of radius <m>\sqrt{1-z}</m>,
    and hence of area <m>\pi(1-z)</m>. As the pancake has thickness <m>\dee{z}</m>,
    it has volume <m>\pi(1-z)\,\dee{z}</m>. So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\pi+2\int_0^1 \dee{z}\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1-z} \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    =\pi+2\int_0^1 \dee{z}\ \pi(1-z)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi+2\pi\left[z-\frac{1}{2}z^2\right]_0^1
    =2\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    
    <exercise>
      <!-- <title><from exam>M317 2012D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p><ol marker="a">
    <li>
      Calculer la divergence du champ de vecteurs <m>\vF = (z + \sin y, zy, \sin x \cos y)</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Calculer le flux de <m>\vF</m> à travers la sphère de rayon  <m>3</m> centrée à l'origine dans  <m>\R^3</m> .
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    le théorème de la divergence,  bien entendu!
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>z</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>0</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a)
    The divergence is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}\big(z+\sin y\big)
         +\pdiff{}{y}\left(zy\right)
         +\pdiff{}{z}\big(\sin x\cos y\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=   z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (b) Let
    <md>
    <mrow>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 9}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    By le théorème de la divergence  (note that we are to find the <em>outward</em>
    flux),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\partial V}  \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot \vF\ \dee{V}
    = \iiint_{\cV} z\ \dee{V}
    = 0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since <m>z</m> is odd.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    La paroi d'un silo à grains est décrite par la portion du cylindre  <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m> avec <m>0 \leqslant z\leqslant 1</m>. Le toit du silo est la portion de la sphère  <m>x^2+ y^2+ z^2 = 2</m> qui se trouve à l'intérieur du cylindre, au dessus du plan <m>xy</m>. Calculer le flux du champ de vecteurs
    <me>
    \vV(x,y,z) = (x^2yz\,,\, yz+e^xz\,,\, x^2+y )
    </me>
    vers l'extérieur du.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    C'est facile d'utiliser théorème de la divergence, mais il ne faut pas oublier la base du silo.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Call the silo <m>\cV</m>.
    Call the sides and top of the silo <m>\cS</m>. Call the base of the silo (namely,
    <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 1</m>, <m>z=0</m>) <m>B</m>. By le théorème de la divergence,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vV\cdot\vn \ \dee{S} + \iint_B \vV\cdot(-\vk )\ \dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vV\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vV\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
            - \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1} (x^2+y)\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}(2xyz+z)\ \dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    By oddness under <m>Y\rightarrow -y</m>,
     <m>\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1} y\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
            = \iiint_{\cV} xyz\ \dee{V}=0</m>, so
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vV\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
    &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1} x^2\ \dee{x}\,\dee{y} +\iiint_{\cV} z\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^1 \dee{r}\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r\ (\overbrace{r\cos\theta}^{x})^2
               +\iiint_{\cV} z\ \dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    We can evaluate the volume integral by decomposing <m>\cV</m>
    into thin horizontal pancakes. See Section 1.6 in the CLP-2 text.
    For <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant 1</m>, the horizontal cross-section of the silo at height
    <m>z</m> is a circle of radius <m>1</m> and hence of area <m>\pi</m>. For <m>z\ge1</m>,
    the horizontal cross-section of the silo at height <m>z</m> is again a
    circle. Its radius is determined by the equation <m>x^2+ y^2+ z^2 = 2</m> of
    the top of the silo. The radius is <m>\sqrt{2-z^2}</m>, so the cross-section
    has area <m>\pi(2-z^2)</m>. The biggest that <m>z</m> can get is <m>\sqrt{2}</m>. Thus
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vV\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^1 \dee{r}\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \ r\ (r\cos\theta)^2+\int_0^1 dz\ \pi z
    +\int_1^{\sqrt{2}}dz\ \pi(2-z^2) z
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\left[\int_0^1 \dee{r}\ r^3\right]
       \left[\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \ \frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}\right]+\int_0^1 dz\ \pi z
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip1in+\int_1^{\sqrt{2}}dz\ \pi(2-z^2) z
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\left[\frac{r^4}{4}\right]_0^1\pi
     +\left[\pi\frac{z^2}{2}\right]_0^1
     +\pi\left[z^2-\frac{z^4}{4}\right]_1^{\sqrt{2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{\pi}{4}+\frac{\pi}{2}+\pi\left[1-\frac{3}{4}\right]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
    <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 \theta\ \dee{\theta}</m>, see Example
    <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cB</m> la boule de volume   <m>V</m> centrée au point <m>(x_0, y_0, z_0)</m>, et soit  <m>\cS</m> la sphère qui est le bord de  <m>\cB</m>. Calculer le flux de <m>\vF = x^2\vi  + xy\vj +(3 z - yz)\vk </m> vers l'extérieur de <m>\cB</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le théorème de la divergence,  bien entendu!
    L'intégraler peut être évaluée facilement grâce au fait que pour tout solide  <m>\cV</m> dans <m>\R^3</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_\cV\dee{V}=\text{Volume}(\cV)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    et
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \bar x =\frac{\iiint_\cV x\,\dee{V}}{\text{Volume}(\cV)}\qquad
    \bar y =\frac{\iiint_\cV y\,\dee{V}}{\text{Volume}(\cV)}\qquad
    \bar z =\frac{\iiint_\cV z\,\dee{V}}{\text{Volume}(\cV)}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    où <m>(\bar x,\bar y,\bar z)</m> est le barycentre <m>\cV</m>.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>[3+3x_0-y_0]\,V</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Apply le théorème de la divergence.  The divergence of <m>\vF</m> is
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF = \pdiff{}{x}(x^2)
    +\pdiff{}{y}(xy)
    +\pdiff{}{z}(3 z - yz)
    =3+3x-y
    </me>
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_B\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_B(3+3x-y)\ \dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To evaluate the integrals of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> we use that, for any solid <m>\cV</m>
    in <m>\R^3</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_\cV\dee{V}=\text{Volume}(\cV)\qquad
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \bar x =\frac{\iiint_\cV x\,\dee{V}}{\text{Volume}(\cV)}\qquad
    \bar y =\frac{\iiint_\cV y\,\dee{V}}{\text{Volume}(\cV)}\qquad
    \bar z =\frac{\iiint_\cV z\,\dee{V}}{\text{Volume}(\cV)}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    where <m>(\bar x,\bar y,\bar z)</m> is the centroid of <m>\cV</m>.
    Our ball has volume <m>\cV</m> and centroid
    <m>(\bar x,\bar y,\bar z) = (x_0,y_0,z_0)</m>.
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    = V[3+3\bar x-\bar y]
    =[3+3x_0-y_0]\,V
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2010D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    On considère le champ
    <me>
    \vF(x, y, z) = \big( 1 + z^{1+z^{1+z}}\,,\, 1 + z^{1+z^{1+z}}\,,\,1\big).
    </me>
    Soit <m>\cS</m> la portion de la surface     <me>
    x^2 + y^2 = 1 - z^4
    </me>
    se trouvant au dessus du plan  <m>xy</m>. Quel est le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers le bas, à travers <m>\cS</m>?
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    La complexité de <m>\vF</m> suggère que le flux ne devrait pas être calculé directement.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>-\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> Let
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1-z^4,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    Then the boundary, <m>\partial V</m>, of <m>\cV</m>, with the orientation
    that is used in le théorème de la divergence,  consists of two parts
    <ul>
    <li>
    the surface <m>\cS</m>, but with the upward pointing normal, and
    </li>
    <li>
    the disk <m>D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1,\ z=0}</m>, with normal <m>-\vk </m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    So le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    =\iint_{\partial V}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =- \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
      +\iint_D\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    As <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=0</m> and <m>\vF(x,y,0) = \big( 1 \,,\, 1 \,,\,1\big)</m>
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_D\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    =-\iint_D\dee{S}
    =-\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2002A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Utiliser le théorème de la divergence  pour calculer le flux de <m>x\vi +y\vj +2z\vk </m> à travers la portion de l'ellipsoïde
    <me>
    x^2+y^2+2z^2=2
    </me>
    telle que  <m>z\geqslant 0</m>. [Note: l'ellipsoïde <m>\frac{x^2}{a^2}+\frac{y^2}{b^2}+\frac{z^2}{c^2}=1</m> a un volume égal à <m>\frac{4}{3}\pi abc</m>.]
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    La surface n'est pas fermée.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{16}{3}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
     Let <m>\cV</m> be the solid <m>x^2+y^2+2z^2\leqslant 2</m>,
    <m>z\geqslant 0</m>. The surface of <m>\cV</m> consists of the half-ellipsoid
    <m>S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+2z^2=2,\ z\geqslant 0}</m>, on top with upward pointing normal,
    and the disk <m>D=\set{(x,y,z)}{z=0,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 2}</m>, on the bottom with
    normal <m>-\vk </m>.
    Call the vector field <m>\vF</m>. By le théorème de la divergence
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
    +\iint_D\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} 4\ \dee{V}
    </me>
    The ellipsoid has <m>a=\sqrt{2}</m>, <m>b=\sqrt{2}</m>, <m>c=1</m> and volume
    <m>\frac{4}{3}\pi abc=\frac{8}{3}\pi</m>. So
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV} 4\ \dee{V}=4\times\half({\rm Volume\ of\ the\ ellipsoid})=\frac{16\pi}{3}
    </me>
    On <m>D</m>, <m>z=0</m> and <m>\iint_D x\,\dee{S}=\iint_D y\,\dee{S}=0</m>
    because <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd.
    So
    <me>
    \iint_D\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    =\iint_D(x\vi +y\vj +0\vk )\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    =0
    </me>
    and the desired flux is
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}=\iiint_{\cV} 4\ \dee{V}
    =\frac{16}{3}\pi
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2010A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\vF(x,y,z) = \vr/r^3</m> où <m>\vr= x\,\vi  + y\,\vj  + z\,\vk </m> et <m>r = |\vr|</m>.
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Calculer  <m>\vnabla \cdot \vF</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur, à travers la surface sphérique <m>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = a^2</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Est-ce que les résultats des parties (a) et (b) contredisent le  théorème de la divergence? Expliquer.
    </li>
    <li>
    Soit <m>\cE</m> la région solide bornée par les surfaces <m>z^2 - x^2 - y^2 + 1 = 0</m>, <m>z = 1</m> et <m>z = -1</m>. Soit  <m>\sigma</m> la surface qui est le bord de  <m>\cE</m>. Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur, à travers <m>\sigma</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Soit <m>\cR</m> la région solide limitée par les surfaces
    <m>z^2 - x^2 - y^2 + 4y - 3 = 0</m>, <m>z = 1</m> et <m>z = - 1</m>. Soit  <m>\Sigma</m> la surface qui est le bord de <m>\cR</m>. Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'estérieur, à travers <m>\Sigma</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (a), (b), (c) Revoir la mise en garde <xref ref="warn_divThm"/>.
    </p>

    <p>(d) le théorème de la divergence peut être utilisé <mdash/> avec précaution.
    </p>

    <p>(e) L'équation gagnerait à être écrite à nouveau en complétant un carré. 
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\vnabla \cdot \vF(x,y,z)=0</m> sauf à <m>(x,y,z)=(0,0,0)</m>, où <m>\vF</m> n'est pas défini.
    </p>

    <p>(b) <m>4\pi</m> </p><p>
    (c) Non.  </p><p>
    (d) <m>4\pi</m> </p><p>
    (e) <m>0</m>
    </p>

    </answer>

    <solution><p> (a)
    If <m>(x,y,z)\ne\vZero</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\vnabla\cdot\vF(x,y,z)
    =\pdiff{}{x}\frac{x}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{3/2}}
    +\pdiff{}{y}\frac{y}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{3/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip1.25in
    +\pdiff{}{z}\frac{z}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{3/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in
    =\frac{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]-x\frac{3}{2}(2x)}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{5/2}}
    +\frac{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]-y\frac{3}{2}(2y)}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip1.25in
    +\frac{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]-z\frac{3}{2}(2z)}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in
    =\frac{3\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]-3x^2-3y^2-3z^2}{{\big[x^2+y^2+z^2\big]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    If <m>(x,y,z)=\vZero</m>, <m>\vF(x,y,z)</m> is not defined
    and hence <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF(x,y,z)</m> is also not defined.
    </p>

    <p>  (b)
    Let <m>a \gt 0</m>. Write
    <m>\sigma_a = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2 = a^2}</m>. The outward unit normal
    to <m>\sigma_a</m> is <m>\vn  = \frac{\vr}{|\vr|}</m> so that
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \int_{\sigma_a}\vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_{|\vr|=a}  \frac{\vr}{|\vr|^3}\cdot \frac{\vr}{|\vr|}\ \dee{S}
    =\int_{|\vr|=a}  \frac{1}{|\vr|^2}\ \dee{S}
    =\frac{1}{a^2}\int_{|\vr|=a}\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{1}{a^2}\big(4\pi a^2\big)
    =4\pi\ne 0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (c)
    No, the results of (a) and (b) do not contradict le théorème de la divergence.
    One hypothesis of le théorème de la divergence  is that <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m>
    (in fact all first order derivatives of <m>\vF</m>) be defined and continuous
    throughout the solid that <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> is to be integrated over.
    That hypothesis is violated in this case.
    </p>

    <p>  (d)
    Let's first figure out what the surface <m>z^2 - x^2 - y^2 + 1 = 0</m>,
    i.e. the surface <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1 +z^2</m>, looks like. For each <m>z_0</m>, the
    <m>z=z_0</m> cross-section of this surface is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1+z_0^2</m>.
    The radius of this circle is <m>1</m> when <m>z_0=0</m> and grows as <m>|z_0|</m>
    increases. So the solid region <m>E</m> looks like an hourglass drum, as sketched
    in the figure on the left below.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="20% 27%" valign="middle">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/hyperboloid1"/>
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/hyperboloidHole"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    We are going to use le théorème de la divergence  to Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m>
    outà travers the surface <m>\sigma</m> of <m>E</m>. However we cannot apply the
    divergence theorem using <m>E</m> as the solid, because <m>\vF</m> is not defined
    at the origin, <m>(0,0,0)</m>, which is a point in <m>E</m>. So we pick any
    <m>0 \lt a \lt 1</m>, and define the auxiliary solid
    <me>
    E_a = \Set{(x,y,z)}{ x^2+y^2+z^2\geqslant a^2,\
                        x^2+y^2\leqslant 1+z^2,\
                        -1\leqslant z\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    The solid <m>E_a</m> is constructed from the solid <m>E</m> by removing
    the ball <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant a^2</m> from it. A side view of <m>E_a</m> is sketched
    in the figure on the right above. As in part (b), denote by <m>\sigma_a</m>
    the surface <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=a^2</m> with <em>outward</em> pointing normal.
    Then the boundary of <m>E_a</m> is <m>\partial E_a=\sigma-\sigma_a</m>, meaning that
    it consists of two parts. One part is the boundary, <m>\sigma</m>, of <m>E</m>,
    with outward pointing normal. The other part is the surface
    <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=a^2</m>, but with normal pointing into the sphere, opposite to the
    normals for <m>\sigma_a</m>. Consequently le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    0=\iiint_{E_a} \vnabla \cdot \vF\,\dee{V}
     =\iint_{\partial E_a} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
     = \iint_{\sigma} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
          -\iint_{\sigma_a} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    so that, by part (b)
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\sigma} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{\sigma_a} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =4\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (e)
    The equation <m>z^2 - x^2 - y^2 + 4y - 3 = 0</m> can be rewritten as
    <me>
    x^2 + (y-2)^2 = 1+z^2
    </me>
    As is part (d), for each <m>z_0</m>, the
    <m>z=z_0</m> cross-section of this surface is a circle <m>x^2+(y-2)^2=1+z_0^2</m>
    of radius <m>\sqrt{1+z_0^2}</m>. But this circle is centred at
    <m>(0,2,z_0)</m>, whereas the corresponding circle in part (d) was centred at
    <m>(0,0,z_0)</m>. The solid <m>R</m> again has the shape of an hourglass drum.
    But while the origin <m>(0,0,0)</m> was in <m>E</m>, it is <em>not</em> in
    <me>
    R=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+(y-2)^2\leqslant 1+z^2,\ -1\leqslant z\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    So <m>\vnabla \cdot \vF=0</m> <em>throughout all</em> of <m>R</m> and the
    divergence theorem gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\Sigma} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{\partial R} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{R} \vnabla \cdot \vF\,\dee{V}
    =0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2009A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Considérer l'ellipsoide <m>\cS</m> donné par
    <me>
    x^2 + \frac{y^2}{4} +\frac{z^2}{4} = 1
    </me>
    orienté par le vecteur normal qui pointe vers l'extérieur.
    </p>

    <p><ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Donner un paramétrage de  <m>\cS</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Calculer le flux  <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}</m> du champ     <me>
    \vF(x,y,z) = (x, y, z)
    </me>
    </li>
    <li>
    Vérifiez votre réponse de (b) avec le théorème de la divergence.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (a) Modifiez convenablement les coordonnées sphériques. N'oubliez pas de bien spécifier le domaine des paramètres.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a)
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\vr(\theta,\varphi)
    =\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
      +2\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
      +2\cos\varphi\,\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;0\le\theta \lt 2\pi,\ 0\leqslant \varphi \leqslant \pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) <m>16\pi</m> </p><p>
    (c) <m>16\pi</m>, à nouveau.
    </p>

    </answer>

    <solution><p> (a)
    If the surface were the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>, we could parametrize
    it using the spherical coordinates  <m>\theta</m> and <m>\varphi</m> (with the radial
    spherical coordinate <m>\rho=1</m>).
    <md>
    <mrow>
    x&amp;=\sin\varphi\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    y&amp;=\sin\varphi\sin\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    z&amp;=\cos\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    with <m>0\le\theta \lt 2\pi</m>, <m>0\leqslant \varphi \leqslant \pi</m>. Our surface is not a sphere,
    but the equation looks like the equation of the sphere with the units of the
    <m>y</m>- and <m>z</m>-coordinates changed. In particular, if we define <m>\tilde y =y/2</m>
    and <m>\tilde z =z/2</m>, so that <m>y=2\tilde y</m> and <m>z=2\tilde z</m>, then on our
    surface
    <md>
    <mrow>
    1=x^2 + \frac{y^2}{4} +\frac{z^2}{4}
     =x^2 + \frac{(2\tilde y)^2}{4} +\frac{(2\tilde z)^2}{4}
     =x^2+\tilde y^2 +\tilde z^2
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and we can parametrize
    <md>
    <mrow>
    x&amp;=\sin\varphi\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    \tilde y&amp;=\sin\varphi\sin\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    \tilde z&amp;=\cos\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and then
    <md>
    <mrow>
    x&amp;=\sin\varphi\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    y&amp;=2\tilde y=2\sin\varphi\sin\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    z&amp;=2\tilde z=2\cos\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    or
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\vr(\theta,\varphi)
    =\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,\vi
      +2\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,\vj
      +2\cos\varphi\,\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;0\le\theta \lt 2\pi,\ 0\leqslant \varphi \leqslant \pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (b) Considering part (c) in this question, we are presumably
    to evaluate the flux integral directly.
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
          \frac{\partial y}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
          \frac{\partial z}{\partial\theta}\Big)
    &amp;=\big(-\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
           2\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\varphi}\,,\,\frac{\partial y}{\partial\varphi}
                 \,,\, \frac{\partial z}{\partial\varphi}\Big)
    &amp;=(\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,2\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,-2\sin\varphi)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>) yields
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\pm\Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
              \frac{\partial y}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
              \frac{\partial z}{\partial\theta}\Big)
    \times
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\varphi}\,,\,\frac{\partial y}{\partial\varphi}
       \,,\, \frac{\partial z}{\partial\varphi}\Big)
    \ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm \big(-\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
           2\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip1.5in\times
    (\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,2\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,-2\sin\varphi)
    \ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm\big(-4\sin^2\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              -2\sin^2\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              -2\sin\varphi\cos\varphi\Big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\mp 2\sin\varphi \big(2\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              \sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              \cos\varphi\Big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get an outward pointing normal we need the <m>+</m> sign. For example, with the
    <m>+</m> sign, the <m>z</m>-component is <m>2\sin\varphi\cos\varphi
    =\sin(2\varphi)</m> so that the normal is pointing upward when
    <m>0 \lt \varphi \lt \frac{\pi}{2}</m>, i.e. in the northern hemisphere,
    and is pointing downward when <m>\frac{\pi}{2} \lt \varphi \lt \pi</m>, i.e.
    in the southern hemisphere. So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF\cdot\vn \dee{S}
    &amp;=\big\{
         (\sin\varphi\cos\theta)(4\sin^2\varphi\cos\theta)
         + (2\sin\varphi\sin\theta)(2\sin^2\varphi\sin\theta)
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2.6in
         + (2\cos\varphi)(2\sin\varphi\cos\varphi)
      \big\}\dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\big\{4\sin^3\varphi\cos^2\theta
      +4\sin^3\varphi\sin^2\theta
      +4\sin\varphi\cos^2\varphi\big\}\dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
     &amp;=4\sin\varphi \big(\sin^2\varphi +\cos^2\varphi\big)
                    \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
     &amp;=4\sin\varphi\,\dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and the flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^\pi\dee{\varphi}\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ 4\sin\varphi
     =8\pi \int_0^\pi \dee{\varphi}\ \sin\varphi
    =16\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (c)
    Set
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)} {x^2 + \tfrac{y^2}{4} +\tfrac{z^2}{4} \leqslant 1}
    </me>
    Since <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=3</m>, le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    = 3 \text{Volume}(V)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    The volume contained in the ellipsoid,
    <m>\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} +\tfrac{z^2}{c^2}=1</m>, of semiaxes
    <m>a</m>, <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> is <m>\frac{4}{3}\pi abc</m>. In our case <m>a=1</m>, <m>b=c=2</m>,
    so
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;= 3 \text{Volume}(V)
    =3\times \frac{4}{3}\pi (1)(2)(2)
    =16\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    which is exactly what we found in part (b).
    </p>

    <p>The volume of the ellipsoid <m>\cV</m> can also be found by observing that,
    in <m>\cV</m>,
    <ul>
    <li>
    <m>x</m> runs from <m>-1</m> to <m>1</m> and
    </li>
    <li> for each fixed <m>-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1</m>, <m>(y,z)</m> runs over the
       disk <m>y^2+z^2\leqslant 4(1-x^2)</m>, which has area <m>4\pi (1-x^2)</m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    That is
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)} {-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1,\  y^2+z^2 \leqslant 4(1-x^2)}
    </me>
    so that
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \text{Volume}(V) &amp;=\int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}
               \iint_{y^2+z^2 \leqslant 4(1-x^2)}\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{-1}^1 \dee{x}\ 4\pi(1-x^2)
      =2\times 4\pi \int_0^1 \dee{x}\ (1-x^2)
      =8\pi\left[1-\frac{1}{3}\right]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{16\pi}{3}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2009A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Calculer l'intégrale de flux <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}</m>, où
    <me>
      \vF(x,y,z) = \big(x^3 + \cos(y^2)\,,\, y^3 + ze^x\,,\, z^2 + \arctan(xy)\big)
    </me>
    et <m>\cS</m> est la surface qui est le bord de la région solide limitée par le cylindre  <m>x^2 + y^2 = 2</m> et les plans  <m>z = 0</m> et <m>z = 2x + 3</m>.
    La surface est orientée positivement, c'est à dire le vecteur normal pointe vers l'extérieur.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    N'évaluez pas le flux directement.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>40\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Set
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 2,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 2x+3}
    </me>
    Let's try le théorème de la divergence. Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}\big(x^3 + \cos(y^2)\big)
         +\pdiff{}{y}\big(y^3 + ze^x\big)
         +\pdiff{}{z}\big(z^2 + \arctan(xy)\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=3x^2+3y^2+2z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>)
    gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 2}\dee{x}\dee{y}\int_0^{2x+3}\dee{z}\
          \big(3x^2+3y^2+2z\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 2}\dee{x}\dee{y}\
          \big\{3(x^2+y^2)(2x+3)+(2x+3)^2\big\}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 2}\dee{x}\dee{y}\
          \big\{9+12x+13x^2+9y^2+6x^3+6xy^2\big\}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 9(2\pi) +\int_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 2}\dee{x}\dee{y}\
          \big\{13x^2+9y^2\big\}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    because <m>12x</m>, <m>6x^3</m> and <m>6xy^2</m> are all odd under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m>.
    To evaluate the final remaining integral, let's switch to polar coordinates.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 2} \big\{13x^2+9y^2\big\}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    &amp;=\int_0^{\sqrt{2}}\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\hskip-5pt\dee{\theta}\
    \big\{13\big(r\cos\theta)^2+9\big(r\sin\theta)^2\big\}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^{\sqrt{2}} \dee{r}\ r^3\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\
    \big\{ 13\cos^2\theta+9\sin^2\theta\big\}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
    &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
    =\left[\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}+\frac{\theta}{2}\right]_0^{2\pi}
    =\pi

    </mrow><mrow>
    \int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
    &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
    =\left[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\right]_0^{2\pi}
    =\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    we finally have
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =18\pi+\frac{(\sqrt{2})^4}{4}\pi\big\{13+9\big\}
    =(18+22)\pi=40\pi
    </me>
    For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
    <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>
    and <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>,
    see Example
    <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2008D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Trouver le flux du champ <m>(x + y, x + z, y + z)</m> à travers la surface cylindrique d'équation <m>x^2 + z^2 = 4</m>, qui s'étend de  <m>y = 0</m> à <m>y = 3</m>. (Seulement la partie courbée, pas les disques Only the curved part à droite et à gauche). La surface est orientée avec le vecteur normal pointant en s'éloignant de l'axe  <m>y</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Pour pratiquer, essayer de faire cet exercice deux fois <mdash/> une avec le théorème de la divergence, puis par calcul direct.
    </p>

    </hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>24\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><title>By divergence theorem</title>
    <p>
    Set <m>\vF = (x + y, x + z, y + z)</m>.
    Then <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF = 2</m>. That's really simple. So let's
    try using le théorème de la divergence.
    </p>

    <p><ul>
    <li><p>
    Set <m>S=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2=4,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 3}</m>. We are to compute
    <m>\iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>, with <m>\vn </m> denoting the outward normal to <m>\cS</m>.
    <m>\cS</m> is <em>not</em> the boundary of a solid, so we cannot compute
    <m>\iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> by applying le théorème de la divergence  directly.
    The figure on the left below shows the part of <m>\cS</m> that is in the first octant.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="50% 49%" valign="middle">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cylinder"/>
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cylinder2"/>
    </sidebyside>

    </li>
    <li>
    On the other hand <m>\cS</m>, is <q>almost</q> the boundary of
    <me>
    V = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2\leqslant 4,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 3}
    </me>
    The boundary, <m>\partial V</m> of <m>\cV</m> consists of three pieces <mdash/> <m>\cS</m> and the
    two disks
    <md>
    <mrow>
    D_l &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2\leqslant 4,\ y=0}
    </mrow><mrow>
    D_r &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2\leqslant 4,\ y=3}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    The figure on the right above shows the parts of <m>\cS</m>, <m>\cV</m>, <m>D_l</m>
    and <m>D_r</m> that are  in the first octant.

    </li>
    </ul>
    The outward normal to <m>D_r</m> is <m>\vj </m> and the outward normal to <m>D_l</m> is
    <m>-\vj </m>, to le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot \vF\,\dee{V}
    &amp;=\iint_{\partial V}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
      + \iint_{D_r}\vF\cdot\vj \,\dee{S}
      + \iint_{D_l}\vF\cdot(-\vj )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Since <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF = 2</m> and <m>\vF\cdot\vj  = x+z</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \iiint_{\cV} 2\,\dee{V}
      -\iint_{x^2+z^2\leqslant 4}\hskip-5pt(x+z)\,\dee{x}\dee{z}
      - \iint_{x^2+z^2\leqslant 4}\hskip-5pt(-x-z)\,\dee{x}\dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \iiint_{\cV} 2\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 2\ \text{volume}(V)
    =2(\pi 2^2) 3 =24\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>
    </solution>

    <solution><title>By direct evaluation</title>
    <p>
    Let's parametrize the surface by
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vr(\theta,y) &amp;= 2\cos\theta\,\vi  +y\,\vj  + 2\sin\theta\,\vk \qquad
    0\le\theta \lt 2\pi,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 3
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Then
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}
    &amp;=\big(-2\sin\theta\,,\,
            0\,,\,
            2\cos\theta \big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}
    &amp;=\big(0\,,\,
           1\,,\,
           0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \vn \dee{S}
    &amp;=\pm\tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta} \times \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial y}
       \dee{\theta}\dee{y}
    =\pm \big(-2\cos\theta\,,\,
           0\,,\,
           -2\sin\theta\big)\dee{\theta}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get the outward normal, we want the minus sign. So
    <me>
    \vn \dee{S}
    =\big(2\cos\theta\,,\,
           0\,,\,
           2\sin\theta\big)\dee{\theta}\dee{y}
    </me>
    and, since
    <me>
    \vF\big(\vr(\theta,y)\big)
    =\big(2\cos\theta + y\,,\,2\cos\theta+2\sin\theta\,,\,y+2\sin\theta\big)
    </me>
    the specified flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\int_0^3\dee{y} \
    \big(2\cos\theta + y\,,\,2\cos\theta+2\sin\theta\,,\,y+2\sin\theta\big)
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in
    \cdot  \big(2\cos\theta\,,\,0\,,\, 2\sin\theta\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\int_0^3\dee{y} \
    \big(4\cos^2\theta + 2y\cos\theta
          +2y\sin\theta+4\sin^2\theta\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\int_0^3\dee{y} \
    \big(4 + 2y\cos\theta +2y\sin\theta\big)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Since <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \cos\theta
     = \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin\theta = 0</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= 4\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\int_0^3\dee{y}
    =4(2\pi)3
    =24\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2008D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    On considère la surface de révolution obtenue en faisant tourner la courbe <m>z=1-x^4</m> autour de l'axe  <m>z</m>. Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion de cette surface qui se trouve au dessus du plan <m>xy</m>, orienté par un vecteur normal qui pointe vers le haut. Le bord de <m>\cS</m> est le cercle de rayon  <m>1</m> centré à l'origine qui se trouve sur le plan <m>xy</m>.
    </p>

    <p>Calculer le flux du champ incompressible
    <m>\vF(x, y, z) = (yz, x + z, x^2 + y^2)</m> à travers <m>\cS</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    La question met l'accent sur le fait que le champ a une divergence nulle. C'est un gros indice. 
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    The question highlights that the vector field has divergence <m>0</m>.
    That strongly suggests that we use le théorème de la divergence.
    Set
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="50% 30%" valign="middle">
    <p><m>V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant z\leqslant 1-\big(x^2+y^2\big)^2}</m></p>
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE08D_10"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Then the boundary, <m>\partial V</m>, of <m>\cV</m> consists of two parts, namely <m>\cS</m>
    (with normal pointing upwards) and the disk
    <me>
    D=\Set{(x,y,0)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    (with normal pointing downwards).  le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>)
    gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
        -\iint_D \vF \cdot (-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_D (x^2+y^2)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Switching to polar coordinates, the flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\int_0^1\dee{r}\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r^2
    =2\pi \int_0^1 \dee{r}\, r^3
    =2\pi \tfrac{1}{4}
    =\tfrac{\pi}{2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2008A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion du paraboloïde  <m>z = 2 - x^2 - y^2</m> contenu dans le cône <m>z = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> et orienté vers le haut. Soit
    <me>
    \vF = (\tan \sqrt{z} + \sin(y^3))\,\vi  + e^{-x^2}\,\vj  + z\vk
    </me>
    Calculer l'intégrale  <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Étant donnée l'allure de <m>\vF</m>, il vaut peut-être mieux de ne pas essayer d'évaluer le flux directement. 
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{3}{2}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    As <m>\vF</m> looks complicated, we will probably want to avoid evaluating
    the flux integral directly. Let's first compute the divergence of <m>\vF</m>,
    to see if it looks wise to use le théorème de la divergence  instead.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF =
       \pdiff{}{x}\big(\tan \sqrt{z} + \sin(y^3)\big)
       +\pdiff{}{y}\big(e^{-x^2}\big)
       +\pdiff{}{z}\big(z\big)
    =1
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Looks good! We cannot yet apply le théorème de la divergence,  since <m>\cS</m> is
    not the boundary of a solid region <m>\cV</m>. To help us choose a solid
    <m>\cV</m> whose boundary at least includes <m>\cS</m>, here is a sketch. <m>\cS</m> is the
    top of the <q>ice cream cone</q>
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="42%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/iceCream"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Note that the paraboloid <m>z = 2 - x^2 - y^2</m> and the cone
    <m>z = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> intersect along the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, <m>z=1</m>.
    Probably the simplest solid whose boundary includes <m>\cS</m> is
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{1\leqslant z\leqslant 2-x^2-y^2,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    The boundary <m>\partial V</m> of <m>\cV</m> consists of <m>\cS</m> (with upward pointing normal)
    and the disk
    <me>
    D = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1,\ z=1}
    </me>
    with normal <m>-\vk </m>. So le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
          -\iint_D \vF \cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}  \overbrace{1}^{\vnabla\cdot\vF}\dee{V}
          +\iint_D \overbrace{1}^{\vF \cdot \vk  = z}\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    As <m>D</m> is a disk of radius 1, <m>\iint_D \dee{S}=\pi</m>. To compute the volume of
    <m>\cV</m>, we'll slice it into a stack of horizontal <q>pancakes</q>. Since
    <m>z=2-x^2-y^2</m> is equivalent to <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}=\sqrt{2-z}</m>, the pancake at height <m>z</m>
    is a circular disk of radius <m>\sqrt{2-z}</m> and hence of cross-sectional area
    <m>\pi(2-z)</m>. So the volume of <m>\cV</m> is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}  \dee{V}
    &amp;=\int_1^2 \pi(2-z) \ \dee{z}
    = -\frac{\pi}{2}(2-z)^2\Big|_1^2
    =\frac{\pi}{2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and the flux
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\frac{\pi}{2} +\pi =\frac{3}{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2007A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Calcule l'intégrale de surface
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    où <m>\vF(x, y, z) = \big(\cos z + xy^2\,,\, xe^{-z}\,,\, \sin y + x^2 z\big)</m> et  <m>\cS</m> est le bord de la région limitée par le paraboloïde <m>z = x^2 + y^2</m> et le plan  <m>z = 4</m>, orientée vers l'extérieur.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Étant donnée l'allure de <m>\vF</m>, ce n'est peut-être pas une bonne idée de calculer l'intégrale de flux directement.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{32}{3}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    As <m>\vF</m> looks complicated, we will probably want to avoid evaluating
    the flux integral directly. Let's first compute the divergence of <m>\vF</m>,
    to see if it looks wise to use le théorème de la divergence  instead.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF =
       \pdiff{}{x}\big(\cos z + xy^2\big)
       +\pdiff{}{y}\big(xe^{-z}\big)
       +\pdiff{}{z}\big(\sin y + x^2 z\big)
    =y^2+x^2
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Looks promising. Furthermore <m>\cS</m> is the boundary of the solid region
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="50% 40%" valign="middle">
      <p><m>V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant z\leqslant 4}</m></p>
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE07A_4"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    So le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV}  (x^2+y^2)\ \dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To compute the triple integral, we'll use the cylindrical coordinates <m>(r,\theta,z)</m>.
    The <m>z</m>-coordinate runs from <m>0</m> to <m>4</m>. For each fixed <m>0\leqslant z \leqslant 4</m>
    (see the blue disk in the figure below <mdash/> which shows the part of <m>\cV</m> in the first octant),
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="50%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE07A_4b"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    <m>(x,y)</m> runs over <m>0\leqslant x^2+y^2 \leqslant z</m>, which in cylindrical coordinates
    is <m>0\leqslant r^2\leqslant z</m> or <m>0\leqslant r\le\sqrt{z}</m>.
    So the flux and the triple integral are
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}  (x^2+y^2)\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^4\dee{z}\int_0^{\sqrt{z}}\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\   r^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi \int_0^4\dee{z}\int_0^{\sqrt{z}}\dee{r}\ r^3
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi \int_0^4\dee{z}\ \frac{z^2}{4}
    =2\pi \frac{4^3}{3\times 4}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{32}{3}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2006D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion de la sphère  <m>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 4</m> comprise entre les plans <m>z = 1</m> et <m>z = 0</m> orientée vers l'extérieur. Soit
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF = (e^y + xz)\,\vi  + (zy + \sin(x))\,\vj  + (z^2 - 1)\,\vk
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Calculer l'intégrale de flux
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}.
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le champ  <m>\vF</m> a l'air pas mal compliqué. Essayer d'éviter le calcul de l'intégrale de flux.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>3\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    If we were to evaluate this integral directly using, for example,
    spherical coordinates, our integrand would contain
    <me>
    \sin(x) = \sin\big(2\sin\varphi\cos\theta\big)
    </me>
    That's not very friendly looking. So let's consider using the divergence
    theorem instead. To start,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}\big(e^y + xz\big)
         +\pdiff{}{y}\big(zy + \sin(x)\big)
         +\pdiff{}{z}\big(z^2 - 1\big)
       = 4z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    That's nice and simple. So let's move on to consideration of <m>\cS</m>.
    The part of <m>\cS</m> in the first octant is outlined in red in the figure
    on the left below.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="43% 43%" valign="middle">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE06D_4"/>
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE06D_4b"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    The surface <m>\cS</m> is not closed, and so is not the boundary of a solid,
    so we cannot apply le théorème de la divergence  directly. But we can easily
    come up with a solid whose boundary contains <m>\cS</m>. Let
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{ x^2 + y^2 + z^2 \leqslant 4,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    The boundary <m>\partial V</m> of <m>\cV</m> consists of three parts <mdash/> <m>\cS</m>,
    the bottom disk
    <me>
    D_b = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2 + y^2 \leqslant 4,\ z=0}
    </me>
    and the top disk
    <me>
    D_t = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2 + y^2 \leqslant 3,\ z=1}
    </me>
    The outward normal to <m>D_t</m> is <m>\vk </m> and the outward normal to <m>D_b</m> is <m>-\vk </m>.
    So le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    &amp;=\iint_{\partial V} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
      +\iint_{D_t} \vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{S}
      +\iint_{D_b} \vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    On <m>D_b</m>, <m>z=0</m> so that <m>\vF\cdot(-\vk ) = -(0^2-1)=1</m> and
    on <m>D_t</m>, <m>z=1</m> so that <m>\vF\cdot\vk  = 1^2-1=0</m>.
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\overbrace{4z}^{\vnabla\cdot\vF}\,\dee{V}
       -\iint_{D_b} \dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    The constant <m>z</m> cross-section of <m>\cV</m> is a disk of radius <m>\sqrt{4-z^2}</m>
    and hence of area <m>\pi(4-z^2)</m> and <m>D_b</m> is a disk of radius <m>2</m> and hence
    of area <m>4\pi</m>. So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^1 (4z)\ \pi(4-z^2) \ \dee{z}  -4\pi
    =4\pi\Big[2z^2 - \frac{z^4}{4}\Big]_0^1 -4\pi
    =3\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2006A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cB</m> la région solide comprise entre les plans <m>x=-1</m>,
    <m>x=1</m>, <m>y=0</m>, <m>y=2</m> et bornée en dessous par le plan  <m>z=0</m> et au dessus par le plan  <m>z+y=3</m>. Soit  <m>\cS</m> le bord de <m>\cB</m>. Calculer le flux du champ
    <me>
    \vF(x,y,z) =  \big(x^2 z +\cos \pi y\big)\,\vi
                 +\big(yz +\sin \pi z\big)\,\vj
                 +(x-y^2)\,\vk
    </me>
    à travers <m>\cS</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    La divergence de  <m>\vF</m> est pas mal plus simple que  <m>\vF</m> lui-même. Par défaut, on veut le flux vers l'extérieur.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{26}{3}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    The divergence of <m>\vF</m>, namely,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}\big(x^2 z +\cos \pi y\big)
         +\pdiff{}{y}\big(yz +\sin \pi z\big)
         +\pdiff{}{z}\big(x-y^2\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;=2xz +z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    is a lot simpler than <m>\vF</m> itself. So let's use le théorème de la divergence
    (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>).
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_B \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_B (2xz+z)\,\dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    As <m>B</m> is invariant under <m>x\rightarrow-x</m> while <m>2xz</m> is odd under
    <m>x\rightarrow-x</m>, the integral <m>\iiint_B 2xz\,\dee{V}</m> is zero.
    To help set up the limits of integration for <m>\iiint_B z\,\dee{V}</m>,
    note that, in <m>B</m>,
    <ul>
    <li>
    <m>(x,y)</m> runs over the rectangle <m>-1\leqslant x\leqslant 1</m>, <m>0\leqslant y\leqslant 2</m> and
    </li>
    <li>
    for each fixed <m>(x,y)</m>, <m>z</m> runs over <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant 3-y</m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \int_{-1}^1\dee{x}\int_0^2\dee{y}\int_0^{3-y}\dee{z}\ z
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \frac{1}{2}\int_{-1}^1\dee{x}\int_0^2\dee{y}\ (3-y)^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{1}{2}\int_{-1}^1\dee{x}\int_3^1\dee{u}\ u^2 \qquad
    \text{with } u = 3-y,\ \dee{u}=-\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{1}{2}\int_{-1}^1\dee{x}\
           \Big[\frac{1^3}{3} - \frac{3^3}{3}\Big]_{-1}^1
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{26}{3}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2005D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> l'hémisphère <m>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 1</m>, <m>z\geqslant 0</m>, orienté par le vecteur normal qui s'éloigne de l'origine. Calculer l'intégrale
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    </me>
    où
    <me>
    \vF = \big(x + \cos(z^2)\big)\,\vi  + \big(y + \ln(x^2 + z^5)\big)\,\vj
               + \sqrt{x^2 + y^2}\,\vk
    </me>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le champ <m>\vF</m> est compliqué. Ceci suggère fortement de ne pas calculer l'intégrale directement
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>2\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    The vector field <m>\vF</m> looks very complicated.
    That strongly suggests that we not evaluate the integral directly.
    So let's start by computing
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}\big(x + \cos(z^2)\big)
         +\pdiff{}{y}\left(y + \ln(x^2 + z^5)\right)
         +\pdiff{}{z}\big(\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=   2
    </mrow>
    </md>
    That's really simple, which suggest that we use le théorème de la divergence.
    But the surface <m>\cS</m> is not closed, and so is not the boundary of a solid.
    So we cannot apply le théorème de la divergence  directly. But we can easily
    come up with a solid whose boundary contains <m>\cS</m>. Let
    <md>
    <mrow>
    V&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant z\leqslant \sqrt{1-x^2-y^2},\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="30%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE05D_9"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Then the boundary, <m>\partial V</m>, of <m>\cV</m> consists of two parts, namely <m>\cS</m>
    (with normal pointing upwards) and the disk
    <me>
    D=\Set{(x,y,0)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    </me>
    (with normal <m>-\vk </m>).  le théorème de la divergence
    (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>) gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
        -\iint_D \vF \cdot (-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} 2\,\dee{V}
      +\iint_D \sqrt{x^2+y^2}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\ \frac{1}{2}\ \frac{4}{3}\pi 1^3
      +\iint_D \sqrt{x^2+y^2}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Switching to polar coordinates, the flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\frac{4}{3}\pi+\int_0^1\dee{r}\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r
    =\frac{4}{3}\pi + 2\pi \int_0^1 \dee{r}\, r^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{4}{3}\pi + 2\pi \frac{1}{3}
    =2\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2015A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\cE</m> la région solide limitée par le plan <m>z = 4</m> et le paraboloide  <m>z = x^2 + y^2</m>. Soit par ailleurs
    <me>
    \vF = \Big(-\frac{1}{3}x^3 + e^{z^2}\Big)\vi
         + \Big(-\frac{1}{3}y^3 + x\tan z\Big)\vj  + 4z\vk
    </me>
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur à travers le bord de <m>\cE</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Soit <m>\cS</m> la portion du paraboloïde <m>z = x^2 + y^2</m> en dessous du plan <m>z = 4</m> orientée de sorte à ce que le vecteur <m>\vn </m> a une composante  <m>\vk </m> positive.  Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m> à travers <m>\cS</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    </statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le divergence de  <m>\vF</m> est beuacoup plus simple que <m>\vF</m> lui-même.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\frac{64}{3}\pi</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>\frac{128}{3}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a)
    By le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>), the outward flux of <m>\vF</m>à travers the boundary of <m>E</m> is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\partial E}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_E \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_E \big(-x^2-y^2+4\big)\,\dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To evaluate this integral we switch to cylindrical coordinates.
    In cylindrical coordinates
    <me>
    E=\Set{(r\cos\theta\,,\,r\sin\theta\,,\,z)}{0\leqslant z\leqslant 4,\ r^2\leqslant z}
    </me>
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\partial E}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^4\dee{z}\int_0^{\sqrt{z}}\dee{r}\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\
             \big(-r^2+4\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi \int_0^4\dee{z}\int_0^{\sqrt{z}}\dee{r}\ \big(4r-r^3\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi \int_0^4\dee{z}\ \Big(2z-\frac{z^2}{4}\Big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 2\pi\Big[z^2-\frac{z^3}{12}\Big]_0^4
    =2\pi\Big[16-\frac{16}{3}\Big]
    =\frac{64}{3}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) The boundary of <m>\cS</m> consists of two parts <mdash/> <m>\cS</m>, but with downward
    pointing normal, on the bottom and the disk
    <me>
    D =\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=4,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 4}
    </me>
    with normal <m>\vk </m>, on top.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="41%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE15A_6"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    So, by part (a),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \frac{64}{3}\pi =\iint_{\partial E}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=-\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
      +\iint_D \vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
      +\iint_D \overbrace{4z}^{\vF\cdot\vk }\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Since <m>z=4</m> on <m>D</m>, and <m>D</m> is a disk of radius 2,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =-\frac{64}{3}\pi +16\iint_D \dee{S}
    =-\frac{64}{3}\pi +16(4\pi)
    =\frac{128}{3}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2012J</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit le champ de vecteurs
    <me>
    \vF(x,y,z) = \frac{x\,\vi +y\,\vj +z\,\vk }
                      {{[x^2 + y^2 + z^2\big]}^{3/2}}
    </me>
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
       Calculer  <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Soit  <m>\cS_1</m> la sphère
    <me>
    x^2 + (y - 2)^2 + z^2 = 9
    </me>
    orientée vers l'extérieur. Calculer
    <m>\ds \iint_{\cS_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Soit <m>\cS_2</m> la sphère
    <me>
    x^2 + (y - 2)^2 + z^2 = 1
    </me>
    orienteé vers l'extérieur. Calculer     <m>\ds \iint_{\cS_2} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Est-ce que les réponses de (b) et (c) coïncident? Expliquer mathématiquement votre réponse.

    </li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    </statement>

    <hint><p>
    Noter que  <m>\vF(x,y,z)</m> n'est pas défini à <m>(x,y,z)=(0,0,0)</m>.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=0</m> if <m>(x,y,z)\ne\vZero</m> et n'est pas définie si <m>(x,y,z)=\vZero</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(b) <m>4\pi</m> </p><p>
    (c) <m>0</m>
    </p>

    <p>(d) Les intégrales de flux <m>\iint_{S_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> et <m>\iint_{S_2} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> sont différentes, à cause du point <m>(0,0,0)</m>, où <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> n'est pas bien définie et l'origine est contenu à l'intérieur de la région limitée par  <m>\cS_1</m>  mais pas à l'intérieur de celle limitée par <m>\cS_2</m>.
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a) Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \pdiff{}{x}\frac{x}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
    &amp;=\frac{1}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
                -\frac{3}{2}\frac{x(2x)}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{-2x^2+y^2+z^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{}{y}\frac{y}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
    &amp;=\frac{1}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
                -\frac{3}{2}\frac{y(2y)}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{x^2-2y^2+z^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{}{z}\frac{z}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
    &amp;=\frac{1}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{3/2}}
                -\frac{3}{2}\frac{z(2z)}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{x^2+y^2-2z^2}{{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    the specified divergence is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
               &amp;=  \frac{(-2x^2+y^2+z^2) + (x^2-2y^2+z^2) + (x^2+y^2-2z^2)}
                         {{[x^2+y^2+z^2]}^{5/2}}
               =0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    if <m>(x,y,z)\ne\vZero</m> and is not defined if <m>(x,y,z)=\vZero</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(b), (c) Set
    <md>
    <mrow>
    V_1 &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2 + (y - 2)^2 + z^2 \leqslant 9}
    </mrow><mrow>
    V_2 &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2 + (y - 2)^2 + z^2 \leqslant 1}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Here are side views of both <m>V_1</m> and <m>V_2</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="43% 43%" valign="middle">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE12J_8a"/>
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE12J_8b"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Both <m>V_1</m> and <m>V_2</m> are spherical balls centred on <m>(0,2,0)</m>.
    The difference between them is that <m>V_1</m> has radius <m>3</m> while <m>V_2</m>
    has radius <m>1</m>. In particular <m>(0,0,0)</m> is not in <m>V_2</m>. So <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> is
    well-defined and zero throughout <m>V_2</m> and, by le théorème de la divergence
    (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S_2} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{V_2} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    =0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    On the other hand, <m>(0,0,0)</m> is in <m>V_1</m>. We cannot blindly apply the divergence
    theorem to <m>V_1</m> <mdash/> <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF(x,y,z)</m> is not defined at the point
    <m>(x,y,z)=(0,0,0)</m> in <m>V_1</m>. We can work around this obstruction
    by
    <ul>
    <li>
    choosing a number <m>\rho \gt 0</m> that is small enough that the sphere
    <me>
    S_\rho = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2=\rho^2}
    </me>
    is completely contained inside <m>V_1</m> (for example, <m>\rho=\frac{1}{2}</m> is fine)
    </li>
    <li>
    and then removing the interior of <m>S_\rho</m> from <m>V_1</m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    This produces
    <me>
    V_3 = \Set{(x,y)}{x^2 + (y - 2)^2 + z^2 \leqslant 9,\ x^2+y^2+z^2\ge\rho^2}
    </me>
    whose side view is sketched below.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="43%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE12J_8c"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    The boundary of <m>V_3</m> consists of two parts
    <ul>
    <li>
    the sphere <m>S_1</m>, with outward normal and
    </li>
    <li>
    the sphere <m>S_\rho</m> with <em>inward</em> normal <m>\vn =-\frac{\vr}{|\vr|}</m>
    </li>
    </ul>
    The divergence <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> is well-defined and zero throughout <m>V_3</m>
    so that, by le théorème de la divergence,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    0=\iiint_{V_3} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    =\iint_{S_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
     +\iint_{S_\rho} \vF\cdot\Big(-\frac{\vr}{|\vr|}\Big)\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iint_{S_\rho} \vF\cdot\Big(\frac{\vr}{|\vr|}\Big)\,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{S_\rho} \Big(\frac{\vr}{|\vr|^3}\Big)\cdot\Big(\frac{\vr}{|\vr|}\Big)\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{S_\rho} \frac{1}{|\vr|^2}\,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{S_\rho} \frac{1}{\rho^2}\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{1}{\rho^2}\ 4\pi\rho^2=4\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since <m>S_\rho</m> is a sphere of radius <m>\rho</m> and hence of surface area <m>4\pi\rho^2</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(d) The flux integrals <m>\iint_{S_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> and
    <m>\iint_{S_2} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> are different, because the one point,
    <m>(0,0,0)</m>, where <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> fails to be well-defined and zero,
    is contained inside <m>S_1</m> but is not contained inside <m>S_2</m>.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2016D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\vF</m> le champ de vecteurs
    <me>
    \vF(x,y, z) = \big(y^3 z + 2x\big)\,\vi
                 +\big(3y - e^{\sin z}\big)\,\vj  + \big(e^{x^2+y^2}+ z\big)\,\vk
    </me>
    Calculer l'intégrale de flux   <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> où <m>\cS</m> est la surface qui délimite la région solide
    <me>
    \cE\ :\
    0 \leqslant x \leqslant 2,\quad
    0 \leqslant y \leqslant 2,\quad
    0 \leqslant z \leqslant 2+ y
    </me>
    avec un vecteur normal pointant vers l'extérieur.
    </p></statement>

    <answer><p>
    <m>72</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    The vector field <m>\vF</m> looks pretty complicated. But its divergence
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF = 2 + 3 + 1 = 6
    </me>
    is very simple. So let's use le théorème de la divergence
    (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divVrn"/>). It says
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_E \vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    =\iiint_E 6\ \dee{V}
    =6\ \text{Volume}(E)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    For any fixed <m>0\leqslant X\leqslant 2</m>, the cross-section of <m>E</m> with <m>x=X</m> has side view
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="33%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE16D_8"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    That cross-section has area <m>2\times \frac{2+4}{2}=6</m>. Consequently the
    volume of <m>E</m> is <m>2\times 6=12</m> and
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =6\times 12
    =72
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2017A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Considérer le champ de vecteurs
    <me>
     \vF(x, y, z) = \big(z \arctan(y^2)\,,\, z^3 \ln(x^2 + 1)\,,\, 3z\big)
    </me>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion de la sphère  <m>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 4</m> qui se trouve au dessus du plan  <m>z = 1</m> et orientée vers le bas.
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Calculer la divergence de <m>\vF</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Calculer l'intégrale de flux  <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    La surface <m>\cS</m> n'est pas une surface fermée.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>3</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>-14\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a) The divergence is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\big(z \arctan(y^2)\big)
          +  \pdiff{}{y}\big(z^3 \ln(x^2 + 1)\big)
          +  \pdiff{}{z}\big(3z\big)
    = 3
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) The complexity of <m>\vF</m> and the simplicity of <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m>
    strongly suggest that we use le théorème de la divergence  to evaluate
    <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>. However, <m>\cS</m> is <em>not</em> a closed
    surface and is <em>not</em> the boundary of a solid. The figure on the left below
    is a sketch of the part of <m>\cS</m> in the first octant.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="36% 36%" valign="middle">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE17A_7a"/>
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE17A_7b"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    On the other hand <m>\cS</m> is part of the surface of the solid
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 4,\ z\geqslant 1}
    </me>
    which is sketched on the right above. The boundary of <m>\cV</m> consists of two parts:
    <ul>
    <li>
    the original surface <m>\cS</m>, but with upward, rather than downward, normal and
    </li>
    <li>
    the disk <m>D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{ x^2+y^2\leqslant 3,\ z=1}</m> with normal <m>-\vk </m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    So le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divVrn"/>) gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
       \iint_{\partial V}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
               &amp;= \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
               = 3 \iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \implies
      -\iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S} +\iint_D\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
               &amp;=3\,\text{Volume}(V)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Thus
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S} &amp;= -3\,\text{Volume}(V)
                          + \iint_D\overbrace{-3}^{-\vF\cdot\vk }\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -3\,\text{Volume}(V) -3\,\text{Area}(D)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -3\,\text{Volume}(V) -9\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since <m>D</m> is a circular disk of radius <m>\sqrt{3}</m>. To compute the volume
    of <m>\cV</m>, we slice <m>\cV</m> into thin horizontal pancakes each of thinkness <m>\dee{z}</m>.
    The pancake at height <m>z</m> has cross-section the circular disk
    <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 4-z^2</m>. As this disk has area <m>\pi(4-z^2)</m>, the pancake has volume
    <m>\pi(4-z^2)\,\dee{z}</m>. All together
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \text{Volume}(V)
    &amp;=\int_1^2\dee{z}\ \pi(4-z^2)
    =\pi\left[4z-\frac{z^3}{3}\right]_1^2
    =\pi\left[4-\frac{7}{3}\right]
    =\frac{5\pi}{3}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S} =-3\frac{5\pi}{3}-9\pi
    =-14\pi
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2017D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la sphère  <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=3</m> orientée vers l'intérieur. Calculer l'intégrale de flux
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    où
    <me>
    \vF = \big(xy^2 + y^4z^6\,,\, yz^2+x^4z\,,\,zx^2+xy^4\big)
    </me>
    </p></statement>

    <answer><p>
    <m>-\frac{4\,\pi}{5}\ 3^{5/2}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Let's try le théorème de la divergence. Set
    <me>
    V = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 3}
    </me>
    Then the boundary of <m>\cV</m> is <m>\cS</m>, but with outward pointing normal.
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
       \pdiff{}{x} \big(xy^2 + y^4z^6\big)
     + \pdiff{}{y} \big(yz^2+x^4z\big)
     + \pdiff{}{z} \big(zx^2+xy^4\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=y^2+z^2+x^2
    </mrow>
    </md>
    and because <m>\cS</m> is oriented <em>inward</em>, le théorème de la divergence
    (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>)
    gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
             &amp;=-\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
              = -\iiint_{\cV} (x^2+y^2+z^2)\,\dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Switching to spherical coordinates
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=-\int_0^{\sqrt{3}}\dee{\rho}\int_0^\pi\dee{\varphi}
                 \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \ \rho^4\sin\varphi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-2\pi\left[\int_0^{\sqrt{3}}\dee{\rho}\ \rho^4\right]
          \left[\int_0^\pi\dee{\varphi}\ \sin\varphi\right]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-2\pi\left[\frac{\rho^5}{5}\right]_0^{\sqrt{3}}
          \Big[-\cos\varphi\Big]_0^\pi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{36\sqrt{3}}{5}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Considérer le champ de vecteurs  <m>\vF(x,y,z)
    =-2xy\,\vi +\big(y^2+\sin(xz)\big)\,\vj +(x^2+y^2)\,\vk </m>.
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Calculer <m>\nabla\cdot \vF</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Trouver le flux de <m>\vF</m> à travers la surface <m>\cS</m> définie par     <me>
    x^2+y^2+(z-12)^2=13^2,\ z\geqslant 0
    </me>
    en utilisant le normal qui pointe vers l'extérieur.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>0</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>\frac {625}{2}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    (a) The divergence of <m>\vF</m> is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \nabla\cdot \vF
    &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}\big(-2xy\big)
    +\pdiff{}{y}\big(y^2+\sin(xz)\big)
    +\pdiff{}{z}\big(x^2+y^2\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-2y+2y+0=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b)
    Call the specified surface <m>\cS</m> and set
    <me>
    V = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+(z-12)^2\leqslant 13^2,\ z\geqslant 0}
    </me>
    The boundary, <m>\partial V</m>, of <m>\cV</m> consists of two parts <mdash/>
    <m>\cS</m>, with outward normal, and the disk
    <me>
    D = \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 13^2-12^2=5^2,\ z=0}
    </me>
    with normal <m>-\vk </m>.
    By le théorème de la divergence,  the desired flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \ \dee{s}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\nabla\cdot \vF\ \dee{V} - \iint_D \vF\cdot(-\vk )\ \dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} 0 \ \dee{V} + \iint_D (x^2+y^2) \dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=0 +\int_0^5\dee{r}\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi\frac{5^4}{4} = \frac {625}{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2003A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion de l'hyporboloïde <m>x^2 + y^2 -z^2 = 1</m> se trouvant entre les plans <m>z=-1</m> et <m>z=1</m>. Trouver le flux de
    <m>\vF = (x+e^{yz})\,\vi  +\big(2yz+\sin(xz)\big)\,\vj  +(xy-z-z^2)\,\vk </m> vers l'extérieur de <m>\cS</m>..
    </p></statement>

    <answer><p>
    <m>4\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    The boundary of the solid <m>\cV</m> enclosed by <m>\cS</m> and <m>z= \pm 1</m> consists
    of three pieces: <m>\cS</m>, the top disk
    <me>
    S_1=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2 + y^2 \leqslant 2,\ z= 1}
    </me>
    and the bottom disk
    <me>
    S_2=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2 + y^2 \leqslant 2,\ z= -1}
    </me>
    On <m>S_1</m>, <m>\vn =\vk </m> and
    <me>
    \vF\cdot\vn =\vF\cdot\vk =xy-z-z^2\Big|_{z=1}= xy-2
    </me> so that,
    denoting <m>D=\Set{(x,y)}{x^2+y^2 \leqslant 2}</m>,
    <me>
    \iint_{S_1} \vF \cdot \vn \, \dee{S}
       = \iint_D (xy -2) \,\dee{x}\dee{y}
       =-2\,\text{Area}(D)= - 4 \pi
    </me>
    Here we have used that the integral <m>\iint_D xy \,\dee{x}\dee{y}=0</m>
    because <m>xy</m> is odd under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m>.
    On <m>S_2</m>, <m>\vn =-\vk </m> and
    <me>
    \vF\cdot\vn =-\vF\cdot\vk = -(xy-z-z^2)\Big|_{z=-1}=-xy
    </me>
    so that
    <me>
    \iint_{S_2} \vF \cdot \vn \, \dee{S} = \iint_D (- xy)\,  \dee{x}\dee{y} = 0
    </me>
    By le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn  \dee{S}
    &amp;= \iint_V \vnabla\cdot\vF\, \dee{V} -
     \iint_{S_1} \vF \cdot \vn \, \dee{S}
    - \iint_{S_2} \vF \cdot \vn \, \dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 0 -(- 4 \pi) - 0
    = 4\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}(x+e^{yz})
         +\pdiff{}{y}\big(2yz+\sin(xz)\big)
         +\pdiff{}{z}(xy-z-z^2)
    </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=   1 + 2z -1 -2z
    </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2002A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\vF</m> le champ de vecteurs <m>\vF(x,y,z)=(x^2-y-1)\,\vi +(e^{\cos y}+z^3)\,\vj +(2xz+z^5)\,\vk </m>.
    Calculer <m>\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> où  <m>\cS</m> est la portion de l'ellipsoide <m>x^2+y^2+2z^2=1</m> vérifiant  <m>z\geqslant 0</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    La complexité de  <m>\vF</m> suggère que le flux ne devrait pas être calculé directement.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    <em>Direct Solution.</em>
    The surface is given by the implicit equation
    <m>f(x,y,z)=0</m> with <m>f(x,y,z)=x^2+y^2+2z^2-1</m>. Hence,
     by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSimplicit"/>),
    <me>
    \vn \,\dee{S}=\frac{\vnabla f}{\vnabla f\cdot\vk }\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =\frac{2x\vi +2y\vj +4z\vk }{4z}\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    This <m>\vn </m> has positive <m>\vk </m> component. Assume that it is the desired
    <m>\vn </m>, though this was not specified in the question.
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\times\vF
    &amp;=\det\left[\begin{matrix}
    \vi  &amp;\vj  &amp;\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x} &amp; \tfrac{\partial }{\partial y} &amp;
                    \tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    x^2-y-1 &amp; e^{\cos y}+z^3 &amp; 2xz+z^5
    \end{matrix}
    \right]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-3z^2\,\vi -2z\,\vj +\vk
    </mrow>
    </md>
    we have
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\hskip-10pt\big(-3z(x,y)^2\,\vi -2z(x,y)\,\vj +\vk \big)
       \cdot\frac{2x\,\vi +2y\,\vj +4z(x,y)\,\vk }{4z(x,y)}\ \dee{x}\dee{y}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\Big(-\frac{3}{2}x\,z(x,y)-y+1\Big)\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Since <m>y</m> is an odd function of <m>y</m> and <m>x\,z(x,y)=x\sqrt{\half(1-x^2-y^2)}</m>
    is an odd function of <m>x</m>, they both integrate to zero. Hence
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}1\ \dee{x}\dee{y}
    =\pi
    </me>
    </p>

    <p><em>Tricky Solution.</em>
     Let <m>\cV</m> be the solid <m>x^2+y^2+2z^2\leqslant 1</m>,
    <m>z\geqslant 0</m>. The surface of <m>\cV</m> consists of <m>\cS</m> with upward pointing normal
    and the disk <m>D=\Set{(x,y,z)}{z=0,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}</m> with normal <m>-\vk </m>.
    By le théorème de la divergence,  Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    +\iint_D\vnabla\times \vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vnabla\times\vF\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} 0\ \dee{V}=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Hence
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS}\vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_D\vnabla\times \vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_D \dee{S}
    =\pi
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2001A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la portion de la sphère  <m>x^2+y^2+(z-1)^2=4</m> qui se trouve  au dessus du plan <m>xy</m>. Find the flux of
    <m>\vF=(x^2+e^{y^2})\,\vi +(e^{x^2}+y^2)\,\vj  +(4+5x)\,\vk </m> outward across
    <m>\cS</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <answer><p>
    <m>12\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Let <m>S'</m> be the disk <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 3,\ z=0</m> (with <m>\vn </m> the downward
    pointing normal) and let <m>\cV</m>
    be the portion of the ball <m>x^2+y^2+(z-1)^2\leqslant 4</m> with <m>z\geqslant 0</m>.
    Then, by le théorème de la divergence,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{V}\vnabla\cdot\vF\, \dee{V}
    -\iint_{S'}\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{V}(2x+2y)\, \dee{V}
    +\iint_{S'}(4+5x)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Because <m>x</m> is odd under <m>x\rightarrow-x</m> and <m>y</m> is odd under
    <m>y\rightarrow -y</m>,
    <me>
    \iiint_{V}x\, \dee{V}=\iiint_{V}y\, \dee{V}=\iint_{S'}x\,\dee{x}\dee{y}=0
    </me>
    so that
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =4\iint_{S'}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =4\,\text{Area}(S')
    =4\times \pi\big(\sqrt{3}\big)^2=12\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 1999A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF=xy^2\vi +x^2y\vj +\vk </m> vers l'extérieur, à travers la surface     <me>
    x^2+y^2+z^2=4,\qquad z\geqslant 0
    </me>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le flux peut être calculé directement, mais c'est plus facile d'utiliser le théorème de la divergence.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{188}{15}\pi\approx39.37</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Call the hemisphere <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant \sqrt{4-x^2-y^2}</m>, <m>H</m>.
    Call the bottom surface of the hemisphere <m>D</m> and the top surface <m>\cS</m>.
    The disk <m>D</m> has radius <m>2</m>, area <m>4\pi</m>, <m>z=0</m> and
    the outward normal <m>-\vk </m>, so that
    <me>
    \iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =-\iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =-\iint_D\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =-4\pi
    </me>
    As
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    =\pdiff{}{x}(xy^2)
    +\pdiff{}{y}(x^2y)
    +\pdiff{}{z}(1)
    =x^2+y^2
    </me>
    le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>)
    gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_H\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    -\iint_D\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cR}(x^2+y^2)\ \dee{V}
    -(-4\pi)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To evaluate the remaining integral, let's switch to the
    cylindrical coordinates <m>(r,\theta,z)</m>. In cylindrical coordinates,
    the equation <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m> becomes <m>r^2+z^2=4</m>. So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=4\pi+\int_0^2 \dee{z}\int_0^{\sqrt{4-z^2}}dr\ r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ r^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=4\pi+2\pi\int_0^2 \dee{z}\ \frac{1}{4}\big(\sqrt{4-z^2}\big)^4
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=4\pi+\frac{\pi}{2}\int_0^2 \dee{z}\ (16-8z^2+z^4\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=4\pi+\frac{\pi}{2}\Big[16z-\frac{8}{3}z^3+\frac{1}{5}z^5\Big]_0^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{188}{15}\pi\approx39.37
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 1998D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
     Soit  <m>\cD</m> le cylindre  <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 1</m>, <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant 5</m>. Calculer le flux du champ de vecteurs
    <me>
    \vF=(x+xye^z)\,\vi +\half y^2ze^z\,\vj +(3z-yze^z)\,\vk
    </me>
    vers l'extérieur, à travers la portion courbée du bord de  <m>\cD</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Utiliser le fait que  <m>y</m> est impaire et évaluer quelques intégrales.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>5\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Let <m>S_t</m>, <m>S_b</m> and <m>S_c</m> denote the top, bottom and curved surfaces of
    <m>D</m> respectively. On the top surface, <m>z=5</m> and
    the outward normal to <m>D</m> is <m>\vk </m>, so that
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS_t}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}(15-5ye^5)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =15\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =15\pi
    </me>
    The integral over <m>y</m> was zero because <m>y</m> is odd under <m>y\rightarrow -y</m>.
    On the bottom surface, <m>z=0</m> and
    the outward normal to <m>D</m> is <m>-\vk </m>, so that
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS_b}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =-\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}(3\times 0-0\times ye^0)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =0
    </me>
    Again, the integral over <m>y</m> was zero because <m>y</m> is odd under
    <m>y\rightarrow -y</m>. As
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}(x+xye^z)
    +\half\pdiff{}{y}\big( y^2ze^z\big)
    +\pdiff{}{z}(3z-yze^z)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=(1+ye^z)+yze^z+(3-yze^z-ye^z)
    =4
    </mrow>
    </md>
    le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS_c}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_D\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    -\iint_{\cS_t}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    -\iint_{\cS_b}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_D4\ \dee{V}
    -15\pi-0
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=4\times\pi 1^2\times 5-15\pi
    =5\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Trouver le flux de <m>\vF=(y+xz)\vi +(y+yz)\vj -(2x+z^2)\vk </m> vers le haut, à travers la portion de la sphère  <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=a^2</m> qui se trouve dans le premier ocrant.
    </p></statement>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\left[\frac{\pi}{6}-\frac{1}{3}\right]a^3</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Let <m>V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant a^2, x\geqslant 0, y\geqslant 0,\ z\geqslant 0}</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="44%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/quartSph"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Then <m>\partial V</m> consists of
    <ul>
    <li>
       the <m>x=0</m> face <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{y^2+z^2\leqslant a^2, x=0, y\geqslant 0,\ z\geqslant 0}</m>
       with normal <m>\vn =-\vi </m>,
    </li>
    <li>
       the <m>y=0</m> face <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+z^2\leqslant a^2, x\geqslant 0, y= 0,\ z\geqslant 0}</m>
       with normal <m>\vn =-\vj </m>,
    </li>
    <li>
       the <m>z=0</m> face <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant a^2, x\geqslant 0, y\geqslant 0,\ z= 0}</m>
       with normal <m>\vn =-\vk </m>,
    </li>
    <li>
       and the first octant part of the sphere. Call it <m>\cS</m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    Then
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\big[z+1+z-2z\big]\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} \,\dee{V}=\frac{1}{8}\ \frac{4}{3}\pi a^3
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{1}{6}\pi a^3
    </mrow><mrow>
    \iint_{\Atop{z=0}{\rm face}}\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    &amp;=\iint_{\Atop{z=0}{\rm face}}(2x+0^2)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    =2\int_0^a dr\,r\int_0^{\pi/2}\dee{\theta}\ r\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\int _0^a r^2\,dr
    =\frac{2a^3}{3}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \iint_{\Atop{y=0}{\rm face}}\vF\cdot(-\vj )\,\dee{x}\,\dee{z}
    &amp;=-\iint_{\Atop{y=0}{\rm face}}(0+0z)\,\dee{x}\,\dee{z}
    =0
    </mrow><mrow>
    \iint_{\Atop{x=0}{\rm face}}\vF\cdot(-\vi )\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    &amp;=\iint_{\Atop{x=0}{\rm face}}-(y+0z)\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    =-\int_0^a dr\,r\int_0^{\pi/2}\dee{\theta}\ r\sin\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\int _0^a r^2\,dr=-\frac{a^3}{3}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    By le théorème de la divergence
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    -\iint_{\Atop{x=0}{\rm face}}\hskip-3pt\vF\cdot(-\vi )\,\dee{y}\,\dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1in
    -\iint_{\Atop{y=0}{\rm face}}\hskip-3pt\vF\cdot(-\vj )\,\dee{x}\,\dee{z}
    -\iint_{\Atop{z=0}{\rm face}}\hskip-3pt\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{x}\,\dee{y}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\left[\frac{\pi}{6}-\frac{1}{3}\right]a^3
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\ \vF=(x-yz)\vi +(y+xz)\vj +(z+2xy)\vk \ </m>, puis
    <ul>
    <li>
    <m>\cS_1</m> la portion du cylindre  <m>\ x^2+y^2=2\ </m> qui se trouve à l'intérieur de la sphère  <m>\ x^2+y^2+z^2=4</m>
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\cS_2</m> la portion de la sphère   <m>\ x^2+y^2+z^2=4\ </m> qui se trouve à l'extérieur du cylindre  <m>\ x^2+y^2=2\ </m>
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\cV</m> la région solide limitée par  <m>\cS_1</m> et <m>\cS_2</m>
    </li>
    </ul>
    Calculer
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    <m>\iint_{S_1}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m>  avec <m>\vn </m> pointant vers l'intérieur;    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}</m>
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\iint_{S_2}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m> avec  <m>\vn </m> pointant vers l'extérieur
    </li>
    </ol>
    Utiliser le théorème de la divergence  pour répondre à au moins une des parties (a), (b) ou (c).
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (a) Penser aux coordonnées cylindriques.
    </p>

    <p>(b) Le volume de <m>\cV</m> peut être calculé facilement avec des rondelles horizontales. C'est en fait un exercice de calcul intégral à une variable.
    </p>

    </hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>-8\sqrt{2}\pi</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>8\sqrt{2}\pi</m> </p><p>
    (c) <m>16\sqrt{2}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    (a)
    On the cylindrical surface <m>S_1</m>, use (surprise!) cylindrical coordinates.
    Since the cylinder has radius <m>\sqrt{2}</m>, we may parametrize it by
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vr(\theta,z) &amp;= \sqrt{2}\cos\theta\,\vi  + \sqrt{2}\sin\theta\,\vj  + z\,\vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta,z)
       &amp;= -\sqrt{2}\sin\theta\,\vi  + \sqrt{2}\cos\theta\,\vj
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{z}(\theta,z)
       &amp;= \vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S} &amp;= \pm \pdiff{\vr}{\theta}(\theta,z)\times
                    \pdiff{\vr}{z}(\theta,z)\ \dee{\theta}\, \dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
            &amp;=\pm\det\left[\begin{matrix} \vi  &amp; \vj  &amp;\vk  \\
                              -\sqrt{2}\sin\theta\,\vi  &amp; \sqrt{2}\cos\theta &amp; 0 \\
                                0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
                       \end{matrix}\right]\ \dee{\theta}\, \dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
            &amp;= \pm\big(\sqrt{2}\cos\theta\,\vi +\sqrt{2}\sin\theta\,\vj \big)\
                                       \dee{\theta}\ \dee{z}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get the inward pointing normal, choose the minus sign. So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=
    \big[\sqrt{2}\big(\cos\theta-z\sin\theta\big)\vi
          + \sqrt{2}\big(\sin\theta+z\cos\theta\big)\vj
          + (\cdots)\vk \big]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;
    \hskip2in\cdot
    \big[-\sqrt{2}\cos\theta\,\vi -\sqrt{2}\sin\theta\,\vj \big]\ \dee{\theta}\, \dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-2\big[\big(\cos\theta-z\sin\theta\big)\cos\theta
    +\big(\sin\theta+z\cos\theta\big)\sin\theta\big]\ \dee{\theta}\, \dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-2\, \dee{\theta}\, \dee{z}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    On the intersection of the sphere and cylinder
    <md>
    <mrow>
    z^2=4-x^2-y^2 = 4-2=2
    </mrow>
    </md>
    so <m>z</m> runs from <m>-\sqrt{2}</m> to <m>\sqrt{2}</m> (see the figure below)
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S_1}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =-2\int_{-\sqrt{2}}^{\sqrt{2}}\dee{z}\,\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}
    =-8\sqrt{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) Observe that <m>\vnabla\cdot \vF=3</m>. So
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} 3\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    The horizontal cross-section of <m>\cV</m> at height <m>z</m> is a washer with outer
    radius <m>\sqrt{4-z^2}</m> (determined by the equation of the sphere) and inner
    radius <m>\sqrt{2}</m> (determined by the equation of the cylinder).
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="61%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cylSph"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    So the cross-section has area
    <m>\pi\big(\sqrt{4-z^2}\big)^2-\pi\big(\sqrt{2}\big)^2=\pi\big(2-z^2\big)</m>
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}
    &amp;=3\iiint_{\cV} \,\dee{V}
    =3\int_{-\sqrt{2}}^{\sqrt{2}} \pi\big(2-z^2\big)\,\dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=6\pi \int_{0}^{\sqrt{2}} \big(2-z^2\big)\,\dee{z}
    =6\pi\big(2\sqrt{2}-\frac{2^{3/2}}{3}\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=8\sqrt{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(c)
    By le théorème de la divergence
    <me>
    \iint_{S_2}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot F\,\dee{V}
    -\iint_{S_1}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =16\sqrt{2}\pi
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

  </exercisegroup>
    
  <exercisegroup> 
      <title>Pour aller plus loin</title>
      
      

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\vE(\vr)</m> le champ électrique du à une configuration de charges électriques de densité (de charge)  <m>\rho(\vr)</m>. La loi de Gauss dit que si  <m>\cV</m> est un solide dans  <m>\R^3</m> avec bord (surface) <m>\partial V</m>, alors le flux electrique
    <me>
    \iint_{\partial V}\vE\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}=4\pi Q
    \qquad \text{ où } \qquad Q=\iiint_{\cV}\rho\ \dee{V}
    </me>
    est la charge totale dans  <m>\cV</m>. Ici, comme d'habiture, <m>\vn </m> est le vecteur normal qui pointe vers l'extérieur. Montrer que
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vE(\vr)=4\pi \rho(\vr)
    </me>
    pour tout <m>\vr</m> dans <m>\R^3</m>. Ceci est l'une des équations de Maxwell. Prendre pour acquis que <m>\vnabla\cdot\vE(\vr)</m> et <m> \rho(\vr)</m> sont bien définis et continus partout.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Revoir comment l'équation de la chaleur a été établie.
    </p></hint>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution><p>
    By le théorème de la divergence
    <me>
    \iint_{\partial V}\vE\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vE\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    So by Gauss' law
    <me>
    \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vE\,\dee{V}=4\pi\iiint_{\cV}\rho\ \dee{V}
    \quad\implies\quad
    \iiint_{\cV}\big[\vnabla\cdot\vE-4\pi\rho\big]\,\dee{V}=0
    </me>
    This is true for all solids <m>\cV</m> for which le théorème de la divergence  applies.
    If there were some point in <m>\R^3</m> for which <m>\vnabla\cdot\vE-4\pi\rho</m>
    were, say, strictly bigger than zero, then, by continuity, we could find a ball
    <m>B_\epsilon</m> centered on that point with <m>\vnabla\cdot\vE-4\pi\rho \gt 0</m> everywhere
    on <m>B_\epsilon</m>. This would force  <m>\iiint_{B_\epsilon}\big[\vnabla\cdot\vE-4\pi\rho\big]\,\dee{V} \gt 0</m>,
    which violates <m>\iiint_{\cV}\big[\vnabla\cdot\vE-4\pi\rho\big]\,\dee{V}=0</m> with <m>\cV</m>
    set equal to <m>B_\epsilon</m>. Hence <m>\vnabla\cdot\vE-4\pi\rho</m> must be zero everywhere.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cV</m> une région solide dans  <m>\R^3</m> dont le bord  est <m>\partial \cV</m>. Montrer que
    <me>
    \iint_{\partial V}\vr\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}=3\,\text{Volume}(V)
    </me>
    où <m>\vr=x\,\vi +y\,\vj +z\,\vk </m> et, comme d'habitude <m>\vn </m> est le vecteur normal à  <m>\partial \cV</m> qui pointe vers l'extérieur. Expiquer géométriquement ce résultat.
    </p></statement>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution><p>
     By le théorème de la divergence
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\partial V}\vr\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vr\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot(x\,\vi +y\,\vj +z\,\vk )\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} 3\,\dee{V}
    =3\,\text{Volume}(V)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Our geometric explanation starts with the observation that
    the volume of the cone with vertex <m>(0,0,0)</m> and base a tiny piece of
    surface <m>\dee{S}</m> is <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> times the area of the base times
    the height of the cone. The height of the cone is <m>|\vn \cdot\vr|</m>,
    where <m>\vr</m> is a point in <m>\dee{S}</m>. So the volume of the cone is <m>\frac{1}{3}|\vn \cdot\vr|\,\dee{S}</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="42%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cone"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    First assume that <m>(0,0,0)</m> is in <m>\cV</m> and <m>\cV</m> is convex.
    Then
    <ul>
    <li>
    <m>\vn \cdot\vr \gt 0</m>, and the volume is  <m>\frac{1}{3} \vn \cdot\vr \,\dee{S}</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    the cone is contained in <m>\cV</m> and
    </li>
    <li>
     <m>\cV</m> is the union of all the tiny conical pieces
    with <m>\dee{S}</m> running over <m>\partial V</m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    So
    <me>
    \text{Volume}(V)=\frac{1}{3}\iint_{\partial V}\vr\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    </me>
    To generalise to the case that  <m>\cV</m> is not convex or <m>(0,0,0)</m> is not in <m>\cV</m>,
    write <m>\cV</m> as the difference between a large convex solid and one or more
    smaller convex solids.
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2016A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\cS</m> la sphère de rayon  <m>3</m> centrée à l'origine orientée vers l'extérieur. Étant donné le champ de vecteurs  <m>\vF(x,y,z) = (0, 0, x + z)</m>:
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Calculer (avec la définition) le flux de  <m>\vF</m> à travers <m>\cS</m>
    <me>
       \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    C'est-à-dire, calculer le flux en évaluant l'intégrale de surface directement.
    </li>
    <li>
       Calculer le même flux avec le théorème de la divergence.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Choisissez un paramétrage judicieux.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a), (b) <m>36\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a)
    We'll parametrize the sphere using the spherical coordinates <m>\theta</m> and
    <m>\varphi</m>.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    x&amp;=3\sin\varphi\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    y&amp;=3\sin\varphi\sin\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    z&amp;=3\cos\varphi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    with <m>0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi</m>, <m>0\le\varphi\leqslant \pi</m>.
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
          \frac{\partial y}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
          \frac{\partial z}{\partial\theta}\Big)
    &amp;=\big(-3\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
           3\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\varphi}\,,\,\frac{\partial y}{\partial\varphi}
                 \,,\, \frac{\partial z}{\partial\varphi}\Big)
    &amp;=(3\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,3\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,-3\sin\varphi)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>) yields
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\pm\Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
              \frac{\partial y}{\partial\theta}\,,\,
              \frac{\partial z}{\partial\theta}\Big)
            \times
    \Big(\frac{\partial x}{\partial\varphi}\,,\,\frac{\partial y}{\partial\varphi}
       \,,\, \frac{\partial z}{\partial\varphi}\Big)
    \ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm \big(-3\sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
           3\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip1.5in\times
    (3\cos\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,3\cos\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,-3\sin\varphi)
    \ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pm\big(-9\sin^2\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              -9\sin^2\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              -9\sin\varphi\cos\varphi\Big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\mp 9\sin\varphi \big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              \sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              \cos\varphi\Big)\ \dee{\theta}\dee{\varphi}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get an outward pointing normal we need the <m>+</m> sign. For example, with the
    <m>+</m> sign, the <m>z</m>-component is <m>9\sin\varphi\cos\varphi
    =\frac{9}{2}\sin(2\varphi)</m> so that the normal is pointing upward when
    <m>0 \lt \varphi \lt \frac{\pi}{2}</m>, i.e. in the northern hemisphere,
    and is pointing downward when <m>\frac{\pi}{2} \lt \varphi \lt \pi</m>, i.e.
    in the southern hemisphere. (As a further consistency check, note that
    <m>\vn (\theta,\varphi)</m> is parallel to <m>\vr(\theta,\varphi)</m>.) So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= 9\!\int_{0}^{2\pi}\hskip-10pt\dee{\theta}\!
    \int_0^\pi\hskip-5pt\dee{\varphi}\,\sin\varphi\,
    (0,0,3\sin\varphi\cos\theta+3\cos\varphi)
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in\cdot
    \big(\sin\varphi\cos\theta\,,\,
              \sin\varphi\sin\theta\,,\,
              \cos\varphi\Big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 27\int_{0}^{2\pi}\hskip-10pt\dee{\theta}
    \int_0^\pi\hskip-5pt\dee{\varphi}\ \big(\sin^2\varphi\cos\varphi\cos\theta
                        +\sin\varphi\cos^2\varphi\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 54\pi\int_0^\pi\hskip-5pt\dee{\varphi}\ \sin\varphi\cos^2\varphi\qquad
    \text{since } \int_0^{2\pi}\cos\theta\ \dee{\theta}=0
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -18\pi \big[\cos^3\varphi\big]_0^\pi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 36\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (b)
    Set
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)\in\R^3}{x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant 9}
    </me>
    Since
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF = \pdiff{}{z}\big(x+z\big)=1
    </me>
    le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>)
    gives
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} \dee{V}
    =\frac{4}{3}\pi 3^3
    =36\pi
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2016A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Considére le cube de côté <m>1</m> qui se trouve dans le premier octant
    (<m>x \geqslant 0</m>, <m>y \geqslant 0</m>, <m>z \geqslant 0</m>) ayant un sommet à l'origine et le somme opposé au point <m>(1, 1, 1)</m>. Un de ses faces se trouve dans le plan <m>x = 0</m>, une autre dans  <m>y = 0</m>, et une troisième dans le plan  <m>z = 0</m>. Les trois autres faces se trouvent dans les plans <m>x = 1</m>, <m>y = 1</m>, et <m>z = 1</m>.
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> la surface ouverte formée par les  <m>5</m> faces du cube qui ne se trouvent pas dans le plan <m>z = 0</m>. La surface  <m>\cS</m> est orientée de sorte que le normal uniatire pointe vers l'extérieur du cube. Trouver la valeur de
    <me>
    I=\iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    </me>
    où <m>\vF</m> est le champ de vecteurs
    <me>
    \vF = \left(y \cos(y^2) + z - 1\,,\, \frac{z}{x+1}+1\,,\, xy e^{z^2}\right)
    </me>
    </p>

    </statement>

    <hint><p>
    Ne pas évaluer l'intégrale directement.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{e}{4}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Denote by <m>\cV</m> the cube specified in the problem. Then <m>\partial V</m>
    consists of <m>\cS</m> together with the face <m>F</m> in the plane <m>z=0</m>, oriented
    with the normal being <m>-\vk </m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="37%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cubeP"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    As
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF &amp;=
        \pdiff{}{x}\big(y \cos(y^2) + z - 1\big)
         +\pdiff{}{y}\left(\frac{z}{x+1}+1\right)
         +\pdiff{}{z}\big(xy e^{z^2}\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
       &amp;=   \pdiff{}{z}\big(xy e^{z^2}\big)

    </mrow>
    </md>
    le théorème de la divergence  (Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>)
    gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
        -\iint_F \vF \cdot (-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\int_0^1\dee{z}\
          \pdiff{}{z}\big(xy e^{z^2}\big)
      +\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\ xy e^{z^2}\Big|_{z=0}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\ xy e^{z^2}\Big|_{z=0}^{z=1}
    +\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\ xy e^{z^2}\Big|_{z=0}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{x}\int_0^1\dee{y}\ xy e^{z^2}\Big|_{z=1}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=e\left[\frac{x^2}{2}\right]_0^1\ \left[\frac{y^2}{2}\right]_0^1
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\frac{e}{4}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2013D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p><ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Trouver un vecteur normal unitaire à la surface <m>z = xy</m> pointant vers le haut, au point  <m>(1, 1, 1)</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Considérer maintenant <m>\cS</m>, la portion de la surface  <m>z = xy</m>, qui se trouve à l'intérieur du cylindre  <m>x^2 + y^2 = 9</m>. Calculer le flux vers l'extérieur de du champ <m>\vF = (y, x, 3)</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Trouver le flux de  <m>\vF = (y, x, 3)</m> à travers la surface cylindrique  <m>x^2 + y^2 = 9</m> entre  <m>z = xy</m> et <m>z = 10</m>. L'orientation est celle qui pointe en s'éloignant de l'axe des <m>z</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Il faut faire attention aux vecteurs normaux dans (c). Pour la pratique, essayer de faire (c) de deux façons différentes.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(-1,-1,1)</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>-\tfrac{27\pi}{2}</m> </p><p>
    (c) <m>-\tfrac{81\pi}{2}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>  (a)
    The equation of the surface is <m>G(x,y,z)=z-xy=0</m>. So one normal to the
    surface at <m>(1,1,1)</m> is <m>(\vnabla G)(1,1,1)=(-y,-x,1)\big|_{(x,y,z)=(1,1,1)}
    =(-1,-1,1)</m> and a unit upward pointing normal at <m>(1,1,1)</m> is
    <m>\frac{(-1,-1,1)}{|(-1,-1,1)|}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}(-1,-1,1)</m>.
    </p>

    <p>  (b)
    For the surface <m>G(x,y,z)=z-xy</m>, so that, by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSimplicit"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S} =\pm\frac{\vnabla G(x,y,z)}{\vnabla G(x,y,z)\cdot\vk }\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =\pm (-y,-x,1) \dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    The <q><m>+</m></q> sign gives the upward normal, so the specified upward flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 9} (y,x,3)\cdot (-y-x,1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 9} (3-x^2-y^2)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Switching to polar coordinates, the flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^3\dee{r}\,r\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ (3-r^2)
    =2\pi \int_0^3 \dee{r}\, (3r-r^3)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi \big(\tfrac{3}{2}3^2-\tfrac{1}{4}3^4\big)
    =-\tfrac{27\pi}{2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (c) <em> by direct evaluation:</em>
    Parametrize the specified surface using the cylindrical coordinates <m>\theta</m>
    and <m>z</m>.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    x &amp;= 3\cos \theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    y &amp;= 3\sin \theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    z &amp; = z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    with <m>0\le\theta\leqslant 2\pi</m> and <m>9\sin\theta\cos\theta\leqslant z\leqslant 10</m>.
    Then, using (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{\theta}
     &amp;= \big(-3\sin\theta\,,\, 3\cos\theta \,,\, 0\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{z}
     &amp;= \big(0\,,\, 0 \,,\, 1\big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \pdiff{\vr}{\theta} \times
         \pdiff{\vr}{z}
    &amp;=3\big(\cos\theta\,,\, \sin\theta\,,\,0 \big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \pdiff{\vr}{\theta} \times
         \pdiff{\vr}{z}\dee{\theta}\,\dee{z}
    =3\big(\cos\theta\,,\, \sin\theta\,,\,0 \big)\,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{z}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    (We have taken the <m>+</m> sign in
    <m>\vn \,\dee{S}
    = \pm \pdiff{\vr}{\theta} \times
         \pdiff{\vr}{z}\dee{\theta}\,\dee{z}</m>
    to give the outward pointing normal.)
    So the specified flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \dblInt \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp; = 3\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \int_{9\cos\theta\sin\theta}^{10}\dee{z}\
         \overbrace{\big(3\sin\theta\,,\,3\cos\theta\,,\,3\big)}^{\vF=(y,x,3)}
            \cdot \big(\cos\theta\,,\, \sin\theta\,,\,0 \big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp; = 18\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \int_{9\cos\theta\sin\theta}^{10}\dee{z}\
         \sin\theta\,\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp; = 18\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta} \
         \big[10 -9\cos\theta\sin\theta\big]\sin\theta\,\cos\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp; = -9\times 18\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2\theta\,\cos^2\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\qquad\qquad\text{since} \int_0^{2\pi} \sin\theta\cos\theta\ \dee{\theta}
                     =\frac{1}{2} \int_0^{2\pi}\sin(2\theta)\ \dee{\theta} = 0
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-9\times 18\times\frac{1}{4} \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2(2\theta)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{81}{2}
              \int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\,\frac{1-\cos(4\theta)}{2}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{81}{2}
         \left[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(4\theta)}{8}\right]_0^{2\pi}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -\frac{81}{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
    <m>\int_0^{2\pi}\dee{\theta}\ \sin^2(2\theta)</m> see Example
    <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
    </p>

    <p>  (c) <em> using le théorème de la divergence :</em>
    Note that if <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 9</m>, then <m>|x|\leqslant 3</m> and <m>y\leqslant 3</m> so
    that <m>|xy|\leqslant 9 \lt 10</m>. Set
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \tilde S&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{ x^2+y^2 = 9,\ xy\leqslant z\leqslant 10}
    </mrow><mrow>
    V&amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{ x^2+y^2\leqslant 9,\ xy\leqslant z\leqslant 10}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Note that the boundary, <m>\partial V</m>,  of <m>\cV</m> consists of three parts:
    <ul>
    <li>
    the side <m>\tilde S</m>, with outward pointing normal (which is the surface and
    the normal specified in part (c) of the question)
    </li>
    <li>
    the bottom, which is the surface <m>\cS</m> of part (b), with downward pointing
    normal (which is opposite the normal specified in part (b)) and
    </li>
    <li>
    the top, which is the surface <m>S_T=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 9,\ z=10}</m>,
    with normal <m>\vn =\vk </m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    Here is a sketch of the part of <m>\partial V</m> that is in the first octant.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="35%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE13D_6"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Note that <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=0</m>. So le théorème de la divergence  yields
    <md>
    <mrow>
    0&amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot \vF\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{\tilde \partial V} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{\tilde S} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
       -\iint_{S} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
       +\iint_{S_T} \vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    This implies
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\tilde S} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iint_{S} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
       -\iint_{S_T} \vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\tfrac{27\pi}{2} -\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 9} 3\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -\tfrac{27\pi}{2} -3 \pi 3^2
    =-\tfrac{81\pi}{2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2013D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p><ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Trouver la divergence du champ <m>\vF  = (x + \sin y, z + y, z^2)</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Trouver le flux de <m>\vF</m> à travers l'hémisphère  <m>x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 25</m>,    <m>z \geqslant 0</m>, orienté vers le haut.
    </li>
    <li>
    Donner une surface fermée  <m>\cS</m>, telle que     <m>\iint_{\cS}\vF \cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> soit égale à  <m>-9</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Pour (b), ne pas évaluer le flux directement.

    Pour (c), le flux peut être relié au volume de la région limitée par la surface et le centre de mass de cette région.
    </p>

    </hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF =2+2z</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>\pi\frac{23}{6} 5^3 =\frac{2875}{6}\pi</m>
    </p>

    <p>(c) Soit <m>\cS</m> une surface qui délimite un solide  <m>\cV</m>, orientée vers l'extérieur. Si <m>\bar z = -\frac{9}{2|\cV| }-1</m>, où <m>|\cV| </m> est le volume de <m>\cV</m> et <m>\bar z</m> est la composante  <m>z</m> du barycentre (i.e. centre de masse si la densité est constante) de <m>\cV</m>, alors
    <m>\iint_{S} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}=-9</m>. Une surface qui vérifie ces conditions est le cube unitaire  <m>\big(0,0, -\frac{11}{2}\big)</m>.
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a)
    The divergence of <m>\vF</m> is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    &amp;= \tfrac{\partial }{\partial x}(x+\sin y)
      +\tfrac{\partial }{\partial y}(z+y)
      +\tfrac{\partial }{\partial z}(z^2)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2+2z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (b) Set
    <md>
    <mrow>
    V &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 25,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant \sqrt{25-x^2-y^2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_T &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+z^2 = 25,\ z\geqslant 0}
    </mrow><mrow>
    S_B &amp;= \Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2 \leqslant 25,\ z= 0}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Note that the boundary, <m>\partial V</m>, of <m>\cV</m> consists ot two parts <mdash/>
    <m>S_T</m> with upward normal, and <m>S_B</m> with normal <m>-\vk </m>.
    We are to find the fluxà travers <m>S_T</m> with upward normal. By the
    divergence theorem, it is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S_T} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
         - \iint_{S_B} \vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \iiint_{\cV} (2+2z)\,\dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since <m>\vF\cdot\vk =z^2=0</m> on <m>S_B</m>. We'll compute the volume integral by expressing it as an iterated integral, with the <m>z</m> integration on the
    outside. In <m>\cV</m>, <m>z</m> ranges for <m>0</m> to <m>5</m>. The set of points
    at exactly height <m>z</m> in <m>\cV</m> is  <m>\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 25-z^2}</m>.
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S_T} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \int_0^5\dee{z} \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 25-z^2}
                \dee{x}\,\dee{y}\  (2+2z)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^5\dee{z}\ (2+2z)\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 25-z^2}
    \dee{x}\,\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^5\dee{z}\ \pi(25-z^2) (2+2z)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    since <m>\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 25-z^2} \dee{x}\,\dee{y}</m>
    is the area of a disk of radius <m>\sqrt{25-z^2}</m>. Continuing,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S_T} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \pi\int_0^5\dee{z}\ (50 -2z^2 +50z -2z^3)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi\Big(50\times 5-2\frac{5^3}{3} +50\frac{5^2}{2}-2\frac{5^4}{4}\Big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi 5^3 \Big(2-\frac{2}{3} +5-\frac{5}{2}\Big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \pi\,5^3 \Big(\frac{4}{3}+\frac{5}{2}\Big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi\frac{23}{6} 5^3
    =\frac{2875}{6}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (c)
    To start, consider any closed surface <m>\cS</m> that is the boundary of a
    solid <m>\cV</m>. Use
    <ul>
    <li>
    the outward pointing normal for <m>\cS</m>,
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>|\cV| </m> to denote the volume of <m>\cV</m>, and
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\bar z=\frac{1}{|\cV| }\iiint_{\cV} z\ \dee{V}</m> to denote the <m>z</m>-component
    of the centroid (i.e. centre of mass with constant density) of <m>\cV</m>.
    </li>
    </ul>
    Then, by le théorème de la divergence
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{S} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    =\iiint_{\cV} (2+2z)\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\iiint_{\cV} \,\dee{V} +2\iiint_{\cV} z\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2|\cV|  +2|\cV| \bar z
    </mrow>
    </md>
    This takes the value <m>-9</m> if and only if
    <md>
    <mrow>
     2|\cV| \bar z =-9-2|\cV|  \iff
    \bar z = -\frac{9}{2|\cV| }-1
    </mrow>
    </md>
    One surface which obeys this condition is the unit cube (with outward normal)
    centred on <m>\big(0,0, -\frac{11}{2}\big)</m>.
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2011D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Calculer les intégrales de surface (méthode au choix).
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    <m>\iint_{\cS} z^2\,\dee{S}</m>, si  <m>\cS</m> est la portion du cône
    <m>x^2 + y^2 = 4z^2</m> où <m>0 \leqslant x \leqslant y</m> et <m>0 \leqslant z \leqslant 1</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m>, if <m>\vF = z\vk </m> and <m>\cS</m> est le rectangle de sommets <m>(0, 2, 0)</m>, <m>(0, 0, 4)</m>, <m>(5, 2, 0)</m>, <m>(5, 0, 4)</m>, orienté vers le haut.
    </li>
    <li>
    <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}</m>, où <m>\vF = (y - z^2 )\vi  + (z - x^2)\vj
    + z^2\vk </m> et <m>\cS</m> est la surface qui délimite la boîte  <m>0 \leqslant x \leqslant 1</m>, <m>0 \leqslant y \leqslant 2</m>, <m>0 \leqslant z \leqslant 3</m>, avec le normal pointant vers l'extérieur.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    (b) Plusieurs méthodes pour calculer des intégrales de flux sont à notre disposition. Qu'est-ce que chacune d'elles demanderait? Laquelle est plus facile à utiliser?
    </p>

    <p>(c) Ne pas évaluer pas directement.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\frac{\sqrt{5}\pi}{8}</m>  </p><p>
    (b) <m>20</m>  </p><p>
    (c) <m>18</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a) The constant <m>z</m> cross-section of the cone at height
    <m>0\leqslant z\leqslant 1</m> is a circle of radius <m>2z</m>. So we may parametrize the
    cone by
    <me>
    \vr(\theta,z) = 2z\cos\theta\,\vi  + 2z\sin\theta\,\vj  +z\,\vk
    \qquad 0\le\theta \lt  2\pi,\ 0\leqslant z\leqslant 1
    </me>
    Since
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}
    &amp;=\big(-2z\sin\theta\,,\,
            2z\cos\theta\,,\,
              0 \big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial z}
    &amp;=\big(2\cos\theta\,,\,
           2\sin\theta\,,\,
              1 \big)
    </mrow><mrow>
    \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta} \times \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial z}
    &amp;=\big(2z\cos\theta\,,\,
           2z\sin\theta\,,\,
           -4z\big)
    </mrow>
    </md>
    (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>) yields that
    the element of surface area for this parametrization is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \dee{S} &amp;=
    \big|\tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial\theta}\times
          \tfrac{\partial\vr}{\partial z} \big|\dee{\theta}\dee{z}
    \ =\ 2z\big|(\cos\theta\,,\,\sin\theta\,,\,-2\big)\big|
        \dee{\theta}\dee{z}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\sqrt{5}z\,\dee{\theta}\dee{z}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    In our parametrization the condition <m>x\leqslant y</m> becomes
    <m>2z\cos\theta\leqslant 2z\sin\theta</m>, which, for <m>z \gt  0</m>, is equivalent
    to <m>\tan\theta\geqslant 1</m>.
    So the specified integral is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} z^2\,\dee{S}
    &amp;=2\sqrt{5}\int_0^1\dee{z}\int_{\pi/4}^{\pi/2}\dee{\theta}\ z^3
    =\frac{\sqrt{5}\pi}{2}\int_0^1\dee{z}\ z^3
    =\frac{\sqrt{5}\pi}{8}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (b) Let's first do some strategizing. We have to compute a flux integral over a surface that is not closed. There are two potential sneaky
    attacks that come to mind.
    <ul>
    <li>  The first uses Stokes' theorem. But the flux integral
    in Stokes' theorem  is of the form
    <m>\iint_{\cS} \vnabla\times\vA\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m>. So to be able to apply
    Stokes' theorem in the current problem, <m>\vF</m> has to be of the form
    <m>\vnabla\times\vA</m>. That is, <m>\vF</m> has to have a vector potential.
    We know that in order for <m>\vF</m> to have a vector potential, it must
    pass the screening test <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF=0</m>. Our <m>\vF=z\,\vk </m> fails
    this screening test. So we can't use Stokes' theorem.
    </li>
    <li>  The second uses le théorème de la divergence. But the flux
    integral in le théorème de la divergence  is over the boundary of a solid.
    That is not the case for our <m>\cS</m>. So in order to apply le théorème de la divergence
    in the current problem, we have to enlarge <m>\cS</m> to the boundary of
    a solid. There are many ways to do this. But they all appear
    fairly complicated. So it does not seem wise to use le théorème de la divergence.
    </li>
    </ul>
    So it looks like we have to evaluate the flux integral directly.
    To do so, we have to determine <m>\vn \,\dee{S}</m> for the specified rectangle.
    Look at the sketch of <m>\cS</m> below. It is part of a plane,
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="45%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE11D_7"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    and that plane is invariant under translations parallel to the
    <m>x</m> axis. As the plane does not passà travers the origin, the equation
    of the plane has to be of the form <m>by+cz=1</m>. For <m>(0,0,4)</m> to be on the plane,
    we need <m>c=\frac{1}{4}</m>. For <m>(0,2,0)</m> to be on the plane, we need
    <m>b=\frac{1}{2}</m>. So <m>\cS</m> is contained in the plane
    <m>G(x,y,z) = \frac{y}{2} +\frac{z}{4} =1</m> and
    equation (<xref ref="eq_SUdSimplicit"/>) gives that
    <me>
    \vn \,\dee{S} = \pm\frac{\vnabla G(x,y,z)}{\vnabla G(x,y,z)\cdot\vk }
                           \dee{x}\dee{y}
    =\pm \frac{(0,\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{4})}{\frac{1}{4}} \dee{x}\dee{y}
    =\pm (0,2,1)\, \dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    The problem specifies that the normal is to be upward, i.e. is to have
    a positive <m>z</m>-component. So
    <me>
    \vn \,\dee{S} = (0,2,1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    Again looking at the sketch of <m>\cS</m> above we see, as <m>(x,y,z)</m> runs over <m>\cS</m>, <m>(x,y)</m> runs over
    <me>
    R = \Set{(x,y)}{0\leqslant x\leqslant 5,\ 0\leqslant y\leqslant 2}
    </me>
    Thus our flux integral is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iint_{\cR} \overbrace{\big(4-2y\big)}^{z}\vk \cdot
               \overbrace{(0,2,1)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}}^{\vn \,\dee{S}}
    =\int_0^2\dee{y}\int_0^5\dee{x}\ (4-2y)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^2\dee{y}\ 5(4-2y)
    =5\Big[4y-y^2\Big]_0^2
    =20
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>  (c) The divergence of the given vector field is
    <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF = 2z</m>, which is pretty simple. So let's
    use le théorème de la divergence. If
    <m>V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0 \leqslant x \leqslant 1, 0 \leqslant y \leqslant 2, 0 \leqslant z \leqslant 3}</m>,
    le théorème de la divergence  says that
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \iiint_{\cV} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    = 2\iiint_{\cV} z\,\dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    This integral would be easy enough to evaluate directly, but we don't
    need to. The average value of <m>z</m> (i.e. the <m>z</m>-coordinate of the centre
    of mass with constant density) is <m>\frac{3}{2}</m>, by symmetry. Since <m>\cV</m>
    has volume <m>6</m>, that average value of <m>z</m> is also
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \bar z = \frac{1}{6} \iiint_{\cV} z\,\dee{V} = \frac{3}{2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    So <m>\iiint_{\cV} z\,\dee{V}=9</m>
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF \cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    = 2\iiint_{\cV} z\,\dee{V}
    =18
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2010A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\sigma_1</m> la surface ouverte donnée par  <m>z = 1 - x^2 - y^2</m>, <m>z \geqslant 0</m>.
    Soit <m>\sigma_2</m> la surface ouverte donnée par <m>z = x^2 + y^2 - 1</m>, <m>z \leqslant 0</m>. Soit  <m>\sigma_3</m> la surface plane donnée par <m>z = 0</m>, <m>x^2 + y^2 \leqslant 1</m>. Considérer le champ de vecteurs  <m>\vF = [ a ( y^2 + z^2 ) + bxz ]\,\vi
              + [ c ( x^2 + z^2 ) + dyz ]\,\vj
              + x^2\,\vk </m>
    où <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, et <m>d</m> sont des constantes.
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Trouver le flux de  <m>\vF</m> à travers <m>\sigma_1</m> vers le haut.
    </li>
    <li>
    Trouver les valeurs des constantes <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, et <m>d</m> telles que le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur à travers la surface fermée  <m>\sigma_1 \cup \sigma_3</m> soit nul.
    </li>
    <li>
    Trouvers les valeurs des constantes <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, et <m>d</m> telles que flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur à travers la surface fermée <m>\sigma_1 \cup \sigma_2</m> soit nul.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Pour (b) et (c), écrire soigneusement l'intégrale fournie par le théorème de la divergence.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>\frac{\pi}{4} +\frac{\pi(b+d)}{6}</m>
    </p>

    <p>(b) <m>\iint_{\sigma_1\cup\sigma_3} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> est nulle si et seulement si  <m>d=-b</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(c) <m>\iint_{\sigma_1\cup\sigma_3} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> est nulle pour tous <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, <m>d</m>.
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p> (a) For the surface <m>z=f(x,y)=1-x^2-y^2</m>, with an upwards
    pointing normal,
    <me>
    \vn \,\dee{S} = \big[-f_x(x,y)\,\dee{x} -f_y(x,y) +\vk \big]\dee{x}\dee{y}
                 = \big[2x\,\vi  + 2y\,\vj  +\vk \big]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>).
    So the specified upward flux is
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\iint_{\sigma_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\hskip-5pt
             \big\{[ a ( y^2 + z^2 ) + bxz ]\,\vi
              + [ c ( x^2 + z^2 ) + dyz ]\,\vj  + x^2\,\vk \big\}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip3in\cdot
                \big\{2x\,\vi  + 2y\,\vj  +\vk \big\}_{z=1 - x^2 - y^2}
             \,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\!\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
             \Big\{[2a x( y^2 \!+\! z^2 ) + 2bx^2z ]
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in
              + [2cy ( x^2 \!+\! z^2 ) +2 dy^2z ] + x^2\Big\}_{z=1 - x^2 - y^2}
             \,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Now
    <me>
    \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\hskip-5pt
             \big\{2a x( y^2 + z^2 ) \big\}_{z=1 - x^2 - y^2}
             \,\dee{x}\dee{y} =0
    </me>
    because the integrand is odd under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m> and
    <me>
    \iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\hskip-5pt
             \big\{2cy ( x^2 + z^2 )\big\}_{z=1 - x^2 - y^2}
             \,\dee{x}\dee{y} =0
    </me>
    because the integrand is odd under <m>y\rightarrow -y</m>. So that leaves
    <me>
    \iint_{\sigma_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iint_{x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}\hskip-5pt
             \big\{ 2bx^2z +2 dy^2z  + x^2\big\}_{z=1 - x^2 - y^2}
             \,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    We'll switch to polar coordinates to evaluate the remaining integral.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\sigma_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^1\hskip-5pt\dee{r}\, r\int_0^{2\pi}\hskip-5pt\dee{\theta}\
             \big\{ 2br^2z\cos^2\theta  +2 dr^2z\sin^2\theta
                         + r^2\cos^2\theta\big\}_{z=1 - r^2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Now
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \int_0^{2\pi}\cos^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
    &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{\cos(2\theta)+1}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
    =\left[\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}+\frac{\theta}{2}\right]_0^{2\pi}
    =\pi

    </mrow><mrow>
    \int_0^{2\pi}\sin^2\theta\ \dee{\theta}
    &amp;=\int_0^{2\pi}\frac{1-\cos(2\theta)}{2}\ \dee{\theta}
    =\left[\frac{\theta}{2}-\frac{\sin(2\theta)}{4}\right]_0^{2\pi}
    =\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
    <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>
    and <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>,
    see Example
    <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
    So, we finally have
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\sigma_1} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\int_0^1\dee{r}\,
             \big\{ 2\pi br^3(1-r^2)  +2\pi dr^3(1-r^2)
                         + \pi r^3\big\}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=2\pi b\Big[\frac{1}{4}-\frac{1}{6}\Big]
      +2\pi d\Big[\frac{1}{4}-\frac{1}{6}\Big]
      +\pi\frac{1}{4}
    =\frac{\pi}{4} +\frac{\pi(b+d)}{6}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b), (c) Here is a side view of <m>\sigma_1</m>, <m>\sigma_2</m> and <m>\sigma_3</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="53%">
    <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE10A_5"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Set
    <md>
    <mrow>
    V_b &amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant z \leqslant 1-x^2-y^2,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    </mrow><mrow>
    V_c &amp;=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2-1 \leqslant z \leqslant 1-x^2-y^2,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 1}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Then <m>\partial V_b = \sigma_1\cup\sigma_3</m> and
         <m>\partial V_c = \sigma_1\cup\sigma_2</m>,
    all with outward pointing normals. Since the divergence of <m>\vF</m> is
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF =
      \pdiff{}{x}[ a ( y^2 \!+\! z^2 ) + bxz ]
      +\pdiff{}{y}[ c ( x^2 \!+\! z^2 ) + dyz ]
      +\pdiff{}{z}[ x^2]
    = (b+d) z
    </me>
    le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\sigma_1\cup\sigma_3} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
       &amp; = \iiint_{V_b} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
         = (b+d)\iiint_{V_b} z\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \iint_{\sigma_1\cup\sigma_2} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
       &amp; = \iiint_{V_c} \vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
         = (b+d)\iiint_{V_c} z\,\dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Now on <m>V_b</m>, <m>z\geqslant 0</m> and <m>z \gt 0</m> except on <m>\sigma_3</m>. So
    <m>\iiint_{V_b} z\,\dee{V} \gt 0</m> and
    <m>\iint_{\sigma_1\cup\sigma_3} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> is zero if and only if
    <m>d=-b</m>. That's the answer to part (b).
    </p>

    <p>On the other hand,  <m>V_c</m> is even under <m>z\rightarrow -z</m> so that
    <m>\iiint_{V_c} z\,\dee{V}=0</m>. Consequently
    <m>\iint_{\sigma_1\cup\sigma_3} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> is zero for all <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>,
    <m>c</m>, <m>d</m>.  That's the answer to part (c).
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2005A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cS</m> l'ellipsoïde <m>x^2+2y^2+3z^2=16</m> et <m>\vn </m> son normal unitaire pointant vers l'extérieur.
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Trouver  <m>\iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> si
    <m>\vF(x,y,z)=\dfrac{(x,y,z)-(2,1,1)}{{\big[(x-2)^2+(y-1)^2+(z-1)^2\big]}^{3/2}}</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
    Trouver  <m>\iint_{\cS} \vG\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}</m> si
    <m>\vG(x,y,z)=\dfrac{(x,y,z)-(3,2,2)}{{\big[(x-3)^2+(y-2)^2+(z-2)^2\big]}^{3/2}}</m>.
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Noter que  <m>2^2+2(1^2)+3(1)^2 = 9 \lt 16</m> de sorte que  <m>(2,1,1)</m> se trouve à l'intérieur de <m>\cS</m>, tandis que  <m>3^2+2(2^2)+3(2)^2 = 29 \gt 16</m>, et donc <m>(3,2,2)</m> est à l'extérieur de  <m>\cS</m>.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>4\pi</m>   </p><p>
    (b) <m>0</m>.
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    We will be using le théorème de la divergence  in both parts (a) and <m>b</m>.
    So as a prelimary calculation, let's find the divergence of
    <m>\vH(x,y,z)=\frac{(x,y,z)-(a,b,c)}{{[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-b)^2]}^{3/2}}</m>
    for any <m>(a,b,c)</m>. If <m>(x,y,z)\ne(a,b,c)</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\vnabla\cdot\vH(x,y,z)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in
    =\pdiff{}{x}\frac{x-a}
                   {{[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2]}^{3/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1.5in
    +\pdiff{}{y}\frac{y-b}
                   {{[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2]}^{3/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1.5in
    +\pdiff{}{z}\frac{z-c}
                    {{[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2]}^{3/2}}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in
    =\frac{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2\big]\ -\ (x-a)\ \frac{3}{2}(2(x-a))}
                           {{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2\big]}^{5/2}}

    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1.5in
    +\frac{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2\big]\ -\ (y-b)\ \frac{3}{2}(2y)}
                            {{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2\big]}^{5/2}}

    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1.5in
    +\frac{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+z^2\big]\ -\ (z-c)\ \frac{3}{2}(2(z-c))}
                           {{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2\big]}^{5/2}}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in
    =\frac{3\big[(x\!-\!a)^2+(y\!-\!b)^2+(z\!-\!c)^2\big]\
                   -\ 3(x\!-\!a)^2-3(y\!-\!b)^2-3(z\!-\!c)^2}
                           {{\big[(x-a)^2+(y-b)^2+(z-c)^2\big]}^{5/2}}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.25in=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    If <m>(x,y,z)=(a,b,c)</m>, <m>\vH(x,y,z)</m> is not defined
    and hence <m>\vnabla\cdot\vH(x,y,z)</m> is also not defined.
    </p>

    <p>(b) By the above preliminary computation with <m>(a,b,c)=(3,2,2)</m>,
    <m>\vnabla\cdot\vG</m> is defined and zero for all <m>(x,y,z)\ne (3,2,2)</m>,
    and, in particular for all <m>(x,y,z)</m> in
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+2y^2+3z^2\leqslant 16}
    </me>
    So, by le théorème de la divergence,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vG\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vG\,\dee{V}
    =0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(a) Because <m>(1,1,2)</m> is inside <m>\cV</m>, we cannot use the argument of part (b),
    to conclude that the integral is zero. Let <m>\veps \gt 0</m> be small enough
    that
    <me>
    S_\veps = \Set{(x,y,z)}{(x-2)^2 + (y-1)^2 +(z-1)^2=\veps^2}
    </me>
    is completely contained inside <m>\cV</m>, as in the sketch below.
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="35%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/OE05A_3"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    Set
    <me>
    V_\veps=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+2y^2+3z^2\leqslant 16,\
                    (x-2)^2 + (y-1)^2 +(z-1)^2\ge\veps^2}
    </me>
    The boundary, <m>\partial V_\veps</m>, of <m>\cV</m> consists of two parts <mdash/>
    <m>\cS</m> and <m>S_\veps</m>, with the normals as in the figure above. The divergence
    <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> of <m>\vF</m> is well-defined and zero throughout <m>V_\veps</m>.
    Consequently, le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    0 &amp;= \iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
       = \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
          + \iint_{S_\veps} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    So
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S} = -\iint_{S_\veps} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    The unit normal to <m>S_\veps</m> at the point <m>(x,y,z)</m> on <m>S_\veps</m> is
    <me>
    \vn  =-\frac{1}{\veps}\big[(x-2)\,\vi  + (y-1)\,\vj  +(z-1)\,\vk \big]
    </me>
    (Recall that <m>|(2-1)\,\vi  + (y-1)\,\vj  +(z-1)\,\vk |=\veps</m> on <m>S_\veps</m>.
    So, on <m>S_\veps</m>,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF\cdot\vn
    &amp;= -\frac{1}{\veps}
      \left(\frac{(x,y,z)-(2,1,1)}{{\big[(x-2)^2+(y-1)^2+(z-1)^2\big]}^{3/2}}\right)
    </mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in
      \cdot\big[(x-2)\,\vi  + (y-1)\,\vj  +(z-1)\,\vk \big]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{1}{\veps} \left(\frac{(x-2)^2+(y-1)^2+(z-1)^2}{{\big[(x-2)^2+(y-1)^2+(z-1)^2\big]
                                                            }^{3/2}}\right)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -\frac{1}{\veps^2}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Hence
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS} \vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    = -\iint_{S_\veps}   \left(-\frac{1}{\veps^2}\right)\,\dee{S}
    =\frac{1}{\veps^2} (4\pi\veps^2)
    =4\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2005A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\Om\subset\R^3</m> une région bornée par une surface lisse  <m>\partial\Om</m> et avec normal unitaire  <m>\vn </m>. Montrer que pour tout champ de vecteurs  <m>\vF</m> de classe <m>C^1</m> sur  <m>\Om\cup\partial\Om</m>,
    <me>
    \iiint_\Om \vnabla\times\vF\,\dee{V}
       = -\iint_{\partial\Om} \vF\times\vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    </p></statement>


    <hint><p>
    Voir le <xref ref="thm_divVrn"/>.
    </p></hint>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution><p>
    This was part of Theorem <xref ref="thm_divVrn"/>.
    To prove it apply le théorème de la divergence,  but with
    <m>\vF</m> replaced by <m>\va\times\vF</m>, where <m>\va</m> is any constant vector.
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\iint_{\partial \Omega} (\va\times\vF)\cdot\vn \ \dee{S}
    =\iiint_{\cV}\vnabla\cdot(\va\times\vF)\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.5in
    =\iiint_\Omega\big[\vF\cdot\underbrace{(\vnabla \times \va)}_{=\vZero}
      -\va\cdot(\vnabla\times\vF)\big]\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;\hskip0.5in=-\iiint_\Omega\va\cdot(\vnabla \times\vF)\ \dee{V}
    =-\va\cdot\iiint_\Omega\vnabla \times\vF\ \dee{V}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get the second line we used the vector identity Theorem <xref ref="thm_divIdentities"/>.d.
    To get the third line, we used that <m>\va</m> is a constant, so that
    all of its derivatives are zero. For all vectors
    <m>\va\cdot(\vb\times\vc)=(\va\times\vb)\cdot\vc</m> (in case you don't
    remember this, it was <xref ref="prop-vect-bis"/>.a)
    so that
    <me>
    (\va\times\vF)\cdot\vn
    =\va\cdot(\vF\times\vn )
    </me>
    and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\va\cdot\iint_{\partial \Omega} \vF\times\vn\ \dee{S}
    =-\va\cdot\iiint_\Omega\vnabla \times\vF\ \dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    \implies &amp;\va\cdot\bigg\{\iint_{\partial \Omega} \vF\times\vn\ \dee{S}
    +\iiint_\Omega\vnabla\times\vF\ \dee{V}\bigg\}=0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    In particular, choosing <m>\va=\vi </m>, <m>\vj </m> and <m>\vk </m>, we see that
    all three components of the vector
    <m>\iint_{\partial \Omega} \vF\times\vn\ \dee{S}
    +\iiint_\Omega\vnabla\times\vF\ \dee{V}</m> are zero. So
    <me>
    \iiint_\Omega\vnabla\times\vF\ \dee{V}
    =-\iint_{\partial \Omega} \vF\times\vn\ \dee{S}
    =\iint_{\partial \Omega} \vn \times\vF\ \dee{S}
    </me>
    which is what we wanted show.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2004A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Rappelons que si  <m>\cS</m> est une surface fermée lisse avec normal unitaire  <m>\vn </m>, alors pour toute fonction lisse <m>p(x,y,z)</m> sur  <m>\R^3</m>,
    on a
    <me>
    \iint_{\cS} p\vn \ \dee{s}=\iiint_{\cE} \nabla p\ \dee{V}
    </me>
    où  <m>\cE</m> est la région solide bornée par  <m>\cS</m>. Montrer qu'en conséquence la force totale exercée sur la surface d'un solide immergé dans ungas de pression constante est nulle. La pression agit dans la direction de la normale à la surface.
    </p></statement>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution><p>
    Pressure is force per unit surface area acting normally into
    a surface. So the force per unit surface area is <m>-p\vn </m>. The total force
    acting on <m>\cS</m> is
    <me>
    -\iint_{\cS} p\vn \,\dee{S}=-\iiint_E \nabla p\ \dee{V}
    </me>
    We are assuming that <m>p</m> is a constant, so that <m>\nabla p=0</m> and the
    total force is zero.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2002A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit <m>\vF</m> un champ de vecteurs lisse dans <m>\R^3</m> tel que le flux de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur de la sphère  <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=a^2</m> est égal à  <m>\pi(a^3+2a^4)</m> pour tout <m>a \gt 0</m>.
    Calculer <m>\vnabla\cdot \vF(0,0,0)</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Considérer une constante  <m>a</m> très petite.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Let <m>S_a</m> denote the sphere <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=a^2</m>
    and <m>V_a</m> denote the solid inside it, which is the ball
    <m>x^2+y^2+z^2\leqslant a^2</m>. Then, by le théorème de la divergence,
    Theorem <xref ref="thm_divThm"/>,
    <me>
    \pi(a^3+2a^4)
    =\iint_{S_a}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =\iiint_{V_a}\vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    Now, for very small <m>a</m>, <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF</m> is almost equal to
    <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF(0,0,0)</m> on all of <m>V_a</m>, and
    the integral  <m>\iiint_{V_a}\vnabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}</m>
    will be
    <me>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF(0,0,0){\rm Volume}(V_a)+O(a^4)
    =\frac{4}{3}\pi a^3\vnabla\cdot\vF(0,0,0)+O(a^4)
    </me>
    Here <m>O(a^4)</m> is an error term that is bounded by a constant times <m>a^4</m>.
    This is consistent with the above equation if and only if
    <m>\vnabla\cdot\vF(0,0,0)=\frac{3}{4}</m>.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2018A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\ \vF= (x^2+y^2+z^2)\,\vi +(e^{x^2}+y^2)\,\vj +(3+x+z)\,\vk \ </m> et  soit <m>\cS</m> la portion de la surface  <m>\ x^2+y^2+z^2=2az+3a^2\ </m> telle que  <m>\ z\geqslant 0</m>, orienté en s'éloignant de l'origine. Ici <m>a \gt 0</m> est constante.  Calculer le flux de  <m>\vF</m> à travers <m>\cS</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Dessiner soigneusement une vue latérale de <m>\cS</m>.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>9\pi a^3+9\pi a^2</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    Note that, since <m>z^2-2az = (z-a)^2 -a^2</m>,
    <me>
    S=\Set{(x,y,z}{ x^2+y^2 +(z-a)^2=4a^2,\ z\geqslant 0}
    </me>
    Let <m>\cV</m> be the solid
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{x^2+y^2+(z-a)^2\leqslant 4a^2,\ z\geqslant 0}
    </me>
    It is the interior of the sphere of radius <m>2a</m> centred on <m>(0,0,a)</m>.
    The surface of <m>\cV</m> (with outward normal) is the union of <m>\cS</m>
    (with normal pointing away from the origin)  and the
    disk
    <me>
    B=\Set{(x,y,0)}{x^2+y^2\leqslant 3a^2}
    </me>
    with normal <m>-\vk </m>. Hence, by le théorème de la divergence
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}\vn\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}-\iint_B\vF\cdot(-\vk )\,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV}(2x+2y+1)\,\dee{V}-\iint_B(-3-x)\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Both <m>\cV</m> and <m>B</m> are invariant under <m>x\rightarrow -x</m> and under <m>y\rightarrow
    -y</m>, so <m>\iiint_{\cV}x\,\dee{V}=\iiint_{\cV}y\,\dee{V}=\iint_B x\,\dee{S}=0</m> and
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cV} \,\dee{V}+3\iint_B\,\dee{S}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To evaluate the integral over <m>\cV</m>, we note that <m>z</m> runs from
    <m>0</m> to <m>3a</m> and that the cross section
    of
    <me>
    V=\Set{(x,y,z)}{0\leqslant z\leqslant 3a,\ x^2+y^2\leqslant 4a^2-(z-a)^2,\ z\geqslant 0}
    </me>
    with fixed <m>z</m> is the circular disk <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 4a^2-(z-a)^2
                                                        = 3a^2 +2a z - z^2</m>,
    which has area <m>\pi\big({\sqrt{3a^2+2az-z^2}\,}\big)^2</m>.
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \, \dee{S}
    &amp;
    =\int_0^{3a}\pi\big({\sqrt{3a^2+2az-z^2}\,}\big)^2\,\dee{z}+3\,\text{Area}(B)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi\int_0^{3a}(3a^2+2az-z^2)\,\dee{z}+3\pi(3a^2)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\pi \left(3a^2\times 3a+2a\times\frac{9a^2}{2}-\frac{27a^3}{3}\right)
            +9\pi a^2
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 9\pi a^3+9\pi a^2
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2000D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>u=u(x,y,z)</m> une solution à l'équation de Laplace
    <me>
    \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2} +\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2} +\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial z^2}
    = 0,
    </me>
    dans  <m>\R^3</m>. Soit <m>\cR</m> un solide lisse dans <m>\R^3</m>.
    </p>

    <p><ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Montrer que le flux total de  <m>\vF = \nabla u</m> vers l'extérieur à travers le bord de  <m>\cR</m> est nul.
    </li>
    <li>
    Montrer que le flux total de  <m>\vG = u\nabla u</m> vers l'extérieur, à travers le bord de  <m>\cR</m> vaut
    <me>
    \iiint_\cR \Big[\Big(\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}\Big)^2 +
    \Big(\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\Big)^2 +
    \Big(\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}\Big)^2\Big]\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    </statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le théorème de la divergence ainsi qu'une identité vectorielle dans  <xref ref="thm_divIdentities"/> peuvent être utiles.
    </p></hint>

    <!-- <answer><p>
    See the solution.
    </p></answer> -->

    <solution><p>
    (a)
    Let <m>\cS</m> denote the boundary of <m>\cR</m>.
    Then <q>the total flux of <m>\vF = \nabla u</m> outà travers the
    boundary of <m>\cR</m></q>
    is given by the integral
    <me>
    I = \iint_\cS \vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    </me>
    Thanks to le théorème de la divergence,
    <md>
    <mrow>
    I
    &amp;= \iiint_\cR \nabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    = \iiint_\cR \nabla\cdot\nabla u\,\dee{V}
    = \iiint_\cR \Big(\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}
         +\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}
         +\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial z^2}\Big)\,\dee{V}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b)
    Similarly,
    <q>the total flux of <m>\vG = u\nabla u</m> outà travers the boundary of <m>\cR</m></q>
    equals
    <me>
    J
    = \iint_\cS \vG\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    = \iiint_\cR \nabla\cdot\vG\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    Here <m>\vG = u\vF</m> (using the notation from part<nbsp/>(a)), so by the vector
    identity of Theorem <xref ref="thm_divIdentities"/>.c,
    <me>
    \nabla\cdot\vG
    = \nabla\cdot(u\vF)
    = (\nabla u)\cdot\vF + u(\nabla\cdot\vF)
    </me>
    But <m>\vF = \nabla u</m>, so <m>\nabla\cdot\vF=\Delta u=0</m> as in part<nbsp/>(a), giving
    <me>
    \nabla\cdot\vG = |\nabla u|^2 + 0
    </me>
    In conclusion,
    <me>
    J
    = \iiint_\cR \nabla\cdot\vG\,\dee{V}
    = \iiint_\cR \Big[ \Big(\frac{\partial u}{ \partial x}\Big)^2
       + \Big(\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\Big)^2
       + \Big(\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}\Big)^2\Big]\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2000D</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Soit  <m>\cR</m> la portion du cylindre  <m>x^2 + (y-1)^2 \leqslant 1</m> telle que  <m>0\leqslant z \leqslant y^2</m>; soit  <m>\cS</m> le bord de  <m>\cR</m>. Étant donné  <m>\vF = x^2\,\vi  + 2y\,\vj  - 2z\,\vk </m>,
    <ol marker="a">
    <li>
    Trouver le flux total de <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur à travers <m>\cS</m>.
    </li>
    <li><p>
    Trouver le flux total de  <m>\vF</m> vers l'extérieur  à travers la paroi verticale de <m>\cS</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
    Vous pouvez utiliser <m> \int_0^\pi \sin^{n}\theta\,\dee{\theta}
    = \frac{n-1}{ n}\int_0^\pi \sin^{n-2}\theta\,\dee{\theta}</m>
    pour  <m>n=2,3,4,\ldots</m>.
    </p>
    </li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    </statement>

    <hint><p>
    <m>x</m> est une fonction impaire.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    (a) <m>0</m> </p><p>
    (b) <m>\frac{15}{2}\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    (a)
    This is a classic case for le théorème de la divergence.
    The flux we want equals
    <me>
    I
    = \iint_\cS \vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    = \iiint_\cR \nabla\cdot\vF\,\dee{V}
    = \iiint_\cR (2x + 2 - 2)\,\dee{V}
    = 2\iiint_\cR x\,\dee{V}
    </me>
    The solid <m>\cR</m> clearly has reflection symmetry across the plane <m>x=0</m>.
    So the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the centre of mass of <m>\cR</m>,
    i.e. the average value of <m>x</m> over <m>\cR</m>,
    i.e.
    <me>
    \bar x =\frac{\iiint_\cR x\,\dee{V}}{\iiint_\cR\dee{V}}
    =\frac{\iiint_\cR x\,\dee{V}}{{\rm Vol}(\cR)}
    </me>
    is zero. Hence
    <me>
    I=2\bar x{\rm Vol}(\cR)=0
    </me>
    </p>

    <p><em>Alternatively</em>, here is a direct evaluation of
    <m>2\iiint_\cR x\,\dee{V}</m>. The base region <m>x^2 +(y-1)^2\leqslant 1</m> is
    the circular disk of radius <m>1</m> centred on <m>(0,1)</m>. In polar coordinates
    it is
    <me>
    r^2\cos^2\theta +(r\sin\theta-1)^2\leqslant 1\quad\text{or}\quad
    r^2-2r\sin\theta +1 \leqslant 1 \quad\text{or}\quad
    r\leqslant 2\sin\theta
    </me>
    Because the disk is contained in the upper half plane, the polar angle
    <m>\theta</m> is restricted to <m>0\le\theta\leqslant \pi</m>. So,
    in cylindrical coordinates, the solid <m>\cR</m> is described by
    <me>
    0\le\theta\le\pi,\qquad
    0\leqslant r \leqslant 2\sin\theta,\qquad
    0\leqslant z\leqslant r^2\sin^2\theta
    </me>
    Hence
    <md>
    <mrow>
    I
    &amp;= 2\int_{\theta=0}^\pi \int_{r=0}^{2\sin\theta} \int_{z=0}^{r^2\sin^2\theta}
    (r\cos\theta)\,\dee{z}\,r\,\dee{r}\,\dee{\theta}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 2 \int_{\theta=0}^\pi \int_{r=0}^{2\sin\theta}
    r^4\sin^2\theta\cos\theta\,\dee{r}\,\dee{\theta}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 2 \int_{\theta=0}^\pi\sin^2\theta\cos\theta
               \Big[\frac{2^5\sin^5\theta}{ 5}\Big]\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \frac{64}{5} \int_{\theta=0}^\pi \sin^7\theta\cos\theta\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \frac{64}{5} \Big[\frac{\sin^8\theta}{8}\Big]_{\theta=0}^\pi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 0
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) <em>using part (a):</em>
    We have
    <me>
    \iint_\cS\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    = \iint_{\cal S_{\rm bottom}}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    + \iint_{\cal S_{\rm top}}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    + \iint_{\cal S_{\rm side}}\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    </me>
    On <m>{\cal S_{\rm bottom}}</m>, <m>z=0</m> and the outward unit normal is
    <m>\vn =-\vk </m>, so <m>\vF\cdot\vn  = 0</m>. Hence
    <me>
    \iint_{\cal S_{\rm bottom}}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    = \iint_{\cal S_{\rm bot}} 0\,\dee{S}
    = 0
    </me>
    On <m>{\cal S_{\rm top}}</m>, <m>z=y^2</m>,
    so <m>\vF = (2x,2y,-2y^2)</m> and,
    by (<xref ref="eq_SUdSgraph"/>),
    <me>
    \vn \dee{S}
    = {(0,-2y,1)}\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    Hence (by the Hint)
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cal S_{\rm bot}}\vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \iint_\cD[-4y^2 - 2y^2]\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -6\int_{\theta=0}^{\pi} \int_{r=0}^{2\sin\theta}
    \big(r^2\sin^2\theta\big)\,r\,\dee{r}\,\dee{\theta}

    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -6\frac{2^4}{4}\int_{\theta=0}^{\pi} \sin^6\theta\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-24\frac{5}{6}\int_{\theta=0}^{\pi} \sin^4\theta\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-24\frac{5}{6}\frac{3}{4}\int_{\theta=0}^{\pi} \sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-24\frac{5}{6}\frac{3}{4}\frac{1}{2}\int_{\theta=0}^{\pi}\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -24\Big[\frac{5}{6}\frac{3}{4}\frac{1}{2}\pi\Big]
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -\frac{15}{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    The conclusion is
    <me>
    \iint_{\cal S_{\rm side}}\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    = \iint_\cS\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    - \iint_{\cal S_{\rm top}}\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    - \iint_{\cal S_{\rm bot}}\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    = \frac{15}{2}\pi
    </me>
    </p>

    <p>(b) <em>by direct evaluation:</em>
    Use the polar equation <m>r=2\sin\theta</m> to parametrize <m>\cS_{\rm side}</m>:
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\vr(\theta,t)
    = (r\cos\theta,r\sin\theta,t)
    = (2\sin\theta\cos\theta, 2\sin^2\theta, t),
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;0\le\theta\le\pi,\
    0\leqslant t\leqslant y^2 = 4\sin^4\theta
    </mrow>
    </md>
    Then using (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vF\cdot \vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;= \vF\cdot\Big(\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial \theta}
             \times\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial t}\Big)\,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{t}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}
    4\sin^2\theta\cos^2\theta    &amp; 4\sin^2\theta         &amp; -2t \\
    2(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta) &amp; 4\sin\theta\cos\theta &amp; 0 \\
    0                            &amp; 0                     &amp; 1 \end{matrix}\right]
    \,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{t}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \det\left[\begin{matrix}
    4\sin^2\theta\cos^2\theta    &amp; 4\sin^2\theta
    </mrow><mrow>
    2(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta) &amp; 4\sin\theta\cos\theta \end{matrix}\right]
    \,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{t}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \big[16\sin^3\theta\cos^3\theta - 8\sin^2\theta\big(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta\big)\big]
    \,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{t}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \big[16\sin^3\theta\big(1-\sin^2\theta\big)\cos\theta - 8\sin^2\theta\big(1 - 2\sin^2\theta\big)\big]
    \,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{t}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 8\big[2\sin^3\theta\cos\theta - 2\sin^5\theta\cos\theta - \sin^2\theta + 2\sin^4\theta\big]
    \,\dee{\theta}\,\dee{t}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    so
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\iint_{\cal S_{\rm side}}\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 8\int_{\theta=0}^\pi \int_{t=0}^{4\sin^4\theta}
    \big[2\sin^3\theta\cos\theta - 2\sin^5\theta\cos\theta - \sin^2\theta + 2\sin^4\theta\big]
    \,\dee{t}\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= 32\int_{\theta=0}^\pi
    \big[2\sin^7\theta\cos\theta - 2\sin^9\theta\cos\theta - \sin^6\theta + 2\sin^8\theta\big]
    \,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=32{\Big[2\frac{\sin^8\theta}{8}-2\frac{\sin^{10}\theta}{10}\Big]}_0^\pi
    -32\int_{\theta=0}^\pi \sin^6\theta \,\dee{\theta}
    +64\int_{\theta=0}^\pi \sin^8\theta \,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= -32 \frac{5}{6}\frac{3}{4}\frac{1}{2}\pi
       + 64\frac{7}{8}\frac{5}{6}\frac{3}{4}\frac{1}{2}\pi
    \quad\text{(by the Hint as above)}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \frac{15}{2}\pi.
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    <p>(b) <em>Offset polar alternative:</em>
    We can also parametrize <m>\cS</m> using cylindrical coordinates translated so that the centre of the base of the cylinder, namely <m>(0,1,0)</m>, plays the role of
    the origin. Then, looking at the figure
    </p>

    <sidebyside width="41%">
      <image source = "images/CLP4-figs/pfigs/cylOffset"/>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
    we see that
    <me>
    x = r\cos\theta\qquad
    y=1+r\sin\theta\qquad
    z=z
    </me>
    In these coordinates, the base region, <m>x^2+(y-1)^2\leqslant 1</m>, <m>z=0</m>, of
    the cylinder is <m>0\leqslant r\leqslant 1</m>, <m>z=0</m>. So we can parametrize <m>\cS</m> by
    <me>
    x = \cos\theta,\ y=1+\sin\theta,\ z=t,
    \qquad
    0\le\theta\le2\pi,\
    0\leqslant t\leqslant (1+\sin\theta)^2
    </me>
    By (<xref ref="eq_SUdSparam"/>),
    <md>
    <mrow>
    &amp;\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial t}\times\pdiff{\vr}{\theta}
    = \det\left[\begin{matrix} \vi  &amp; \vj  &amp; \vk
    </mrow><mrow>
    0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1
    </mrow><mrow>
    -\sin\theta &amp; \cos\theta &amp; 0 \end{matrix}\right]
    = \big(-\cos\theta, -\sin\theta, 0\big),

    </mrow><mrow>
    \vn \,\dee{S} &amp;= -\frac{\partial\vr}{\partial t}\times
                \pdiff{\vr}{\theta}\,\dee{t}\,\dee{\theta}
    = (\cos\theta,\sin\theta,0)\dee{t}\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    where we have chosen the sign to give the outward pointing normal.
    So
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_\cS\vF\cdot \vn \dee{S}
    &amp;= \int_{\theta=0}^{2\pi} \int_{t=0}^{(1+\sin\theta)^2}
    \big[\cos^3\theta+2(1+\sin\theta)\sin\theta\big]\,\dee{t}\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^{2\pi}
    \big[ (1+\sin\theta)^2\cos^3\theta
    +2(1+\sin\theta)^3\sin\theta\big]\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;= \int_0^{2\pi}
    \big[ 2\sin\theta\cos^3\theta
    +6\sin^2\theta+2\sin^4\theta\big]\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=-\frac{1}{2}\cos^4\theta\Big|_0^{2\pi}
       +12\int_0^\pi \sin^2\theta\,\dee{\theta}
       +4\int_0^\pi \sin^4\theta\,\dee{\theta}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=0+12\frac{\pi}{2} +4\frac{3}{4}\frac{\pi}{2}
     = \frac{15}{2}\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    To get the third line, we used that the integral over <m>0\le\theta\le2\pi</m>
    of any odd power of <m>\sin\theta</m> or <m>\cos\theta</m> is zero.
    </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise><!-- <title><from exam>M317 2000A</fromexam></title> --> 
    <statement><p>
    Une surface lisse <m>\cS</m> se trouve au dessus du plan <m>z=0</m> et a pour bord le cercle <m>x^2+y^2=4y</m> dans le plan  <m>z=0</m>. Ce cerle délimite aussi un disque  <m>\cD</m> dans ce plan. Le volume de la région solide  <m>\cR</m> limitée par  <m>\cS</m> et <m>\cD</m> est de 10 unités cubes. Trouver le flux de
    <me>
    \vF(x,y,z)=(x+x^2y)\vi +(y-xy^2)\vj +(z+2x+3y)\vk
    </me>
    à travers <m>\cS</m> vers l'extérieur de <m>\cR</m>.
    </p></statement>

    <hint><p>
    Le barycentre <m>(\bar x,\bar y)</m> du disque  <m>\cD</m> devrait être facile à deviner. Alors les intégrales <m>\iint_{\cD} x\,\dee{x}\dee{y}</m> et <m>\iint_{\cD} y\,\dee{x}\dee{y}</m> peuvent être utilisées au moyen de  <m>\bar x = \frac{\iint_{\cD} x\,\dee{x}\dee{y}}{\iint_{\cD} \dee{x}\dee{y}}</m>
    et
    <m>\bar y = \frac{\iint_{\cD} y\,\dee{x}\dee{y}}{\iint_{\cD} \dee{x}\dee{y}}</m>.
    </p></hint>

    <answer><p>
    <m>30+24\pi</m>
    </p></answer>

    <solution><p>
    The circle <m>x^2+y^2=4y</m>, or equivalently, <m>x^2+(y-2)^2=4</m>, has radius
    <m>2</m> and centre <m>(0,2)</m>.
    On the bottom surface, <m>z=0</m> and
    the outward normal is <m>-\vk </m>, so that
    <me>
    \iint_{\cD}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =-\iint_{\cD}\vF\cdot\vk \,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    =-\iint_{\cD}(2x+3y)\,\dee{x}\dee{y}
    </me>
    By symmetry, the centre of mass, <m>(\bar x,\bar y)</m>, of the circle
    is <m>(0,2)</m>. Here <m>\bar x</m> and <m>\bar y</m> are the average values
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \bar x = \frac{\iint_D x\,\dee{x}\dee{y}}{\iint_D \dee{x}\dee{y}}\qquad
    \bar y = \frac{\iint_D y\,\dee{x}\dee{y}}{\iint_D \dee{x}\dee{y}}
    </mrow>
    </md>
    of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> over <m>D</m>.
    As the disk <m>D</m> has area <m>4\pi</m>,
    <me>
    \iint_D x\,\dee{x}\dee{y} =4\pi\bar x =0\qquad
    \iint_D y\,\dee{x}\dee{y} =4\pi\bar y =8\pi
    </me>
    and
    <me>
    \iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    =-4\pi(2\bar x+3\bar y)
    =-4\pi(2\times 0+3\times 2)
    =-24\pi
    </me>
    As
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \vnabla\cdot\vF
    &amp;=\pdiff{}{x}(x+x^2y)
    +\pdiff{}{y}(y-xy^2)
    +\pdiff{}{z}(z+2x+3y)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=(1+2xy)+(1-2xy)+(1)
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=3
    </mrow>
    </md>
    le théorème de la divergence  gives
    <md>
    <mrow>
    \iint_{\cS}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cR}\vnabla\cdot\vF\ \dee{V}
    -\iint_{D}\vF\cdot\vn \,\dee{S}
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=\iiint_{\cR}3\ \dee{V}
    -(-24\pi)
    =3\text{Vol}(R)+24\pi
    =3\times10+24\pi
    </mrow><mrow>
    &amp;=30+24\pi
    </mrow>
    </md>
    </p>

    </solution>
